impact: The score was Davis' first of the season. He was left uncovered on a 22-yarder. Davis will pop up for the occasional big play but won't see enough volume for fantasy relevance in the Redskins' Alex Smith-led offense.
report: Vernon Davis caught 3-of-3 targets for 48 yards and a touchdown in the Redskins' Week 6 win over the Panthers.

impact: Odd. Even without Jamison Crowder and Paul Richardson Sunday, Davis didn't even see one target. Jordan Reed tied backup RB Kapri Bibbs with a team-high 43 receiving yards. Davis will undoubtedly pop if Reed misses time, but should remain on waivers until that day comes.
report: Vernon Davis failed to record a single target in Washington's Week 7 win over the Cowboys.

impact: Walker appeared to dislocate his ankle, or at very least break his leg.  Being the warrior he is, Walker waved to fans as he made his way to the locker room on the cart.  Walker finished the game with four catches for 52 yards.  We don't expect to see him back on the field anytime soon.
report: Delanie Walker was carted off the field with a gruesome ankle/leg injury in the fourth quarter of Sunday's Week 1 game in Miami.

impact: As expected.  Walker had his ankle rolled up underneath a defender, bending it unnaturally, requiring an immediate air cast.  Walker is a warrior but simply can't play through this one.  Walker is signed through 2020 and will be 35 the next time he steps on the field.  Jonnu Smith figures to take over at tight end for the Titans, but Corey Davis is going to gobble up pass-game targets.
report: NFL Network's Ian Rapoport reports Delanie Walker has been diagnosed with a dislocated ankle along with a fracture and is "almost certainly" done for the season.

impact: Smith was reportedly expected to see "plenty of opportunities" without Delanie Walker. In his first post-Walker outing, he was out-targeted 2-0 by Luke Stocker. The Titans won't always have to start their backup quarterback and third-string tackle, so all hope isn't lost for Smith just yet. The 92nd-percentile SPARQ monstrosity will have another week to prove he can produce on a full-time basis.
report: Jonnu Smith didn't receive a target in the Titans' Week 2 win over the Texans.

impact: Smith is a promising talent in theory, but the dysfunctional nature of the passing game in which he plays strips Smith of any streamer appeal in re-draft leagues.
report: Jonnu Smith caught 1-of-2 targets for nine yards in the Titans' Week 3 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Smith continues to play the majority of snaps, but he now has just two catches on seven targets this season. One of his missed connections in this game was a bad drop on third down. He is not an option in redraft leagues.
report: Jonnu Smith did not haul in either of his targets in the Titans' Week 4 win over the Eagles.

impact: Smith has been targeted five times by Marcus Mariota this year, catching none.
report: Titans TE Jonnu Smith was held catch-less on two targets in Week 5.

impact: Smith was tackled just short of the end-zone on one of his catches. He had only three targets, but he's been more involved the last few weeks. The Titans are on a bye in Week 8.
report: Jonnu Smith caught two passes for 11 yards in Week 7 against the Chargers.

impact: Not only did Brate put up a goose egg, but he was also out-snapped 43-24 by teammate and fellow tight O.J. Howard. Dating back to last season, the Harvard alum has totaled an embarrassing 186 yards over his last 10 games. Even at a thin fantasy position, the 27-year-old doesn’t carry much weight.
report: Cameron Brate failed to catch either of his two targets Sunday in the Buccaneers’ Week 1 victory over the Saints.

impact: Catch-less through two weeks, Brate lacks fantasy value behind O.J. Howard.
report: Cameron Brate was held catch-less in Week 2 against the Eagles.

impact: Brate has either been Jekyll or Hyde through the Bucs' first four games, being held catchless in Tampa's first two contests only to cross pay dirt in the next two. O.J. Howard (knee) did get knocked out in the second quarter Sunday and wasn't able to return. Brate has historically performed much better with Jameis Winston under center, and he'll arguably be a TE1 against the Falcons' ailing secondary if Howard remains out after the bye.
report: Cameron Brate caught 3-of-4 targets for 29 yards and one touchdown in the Bucs' Week 4 loss to the Bears.

impact: Even with Howard back, Brate did his fantasy backers proud by catching a touchdown on the opening drive. Jameis Winston showed a lot of trust in his tight end on the throw, and Brate made it count by going up over De’Vondre Campbell for the score. Brate now has a touchdown in three straight games. Unfortunately for his value moving forward, that was his only target as O.J. Howard went for 62 yards. He will be just a TE2 next week against the Browns.
report: Cameron Brate hauled in his only target for a 15-yard touchdown in the Bucs' Week 6 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Brate lost a fumble on one of his three catches that the Bucs were fortunate to not have come back to haunt them. Brate has just 15 targets on the season and only has true fantasy value if something were to happen to O.J. Howard.
report: Cameron Brate caught 3-of-4 targets for 23 yards in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: James drew the start and opportunity with Vance McDonald still sidelined with a foot injury. He will only be a fringe TE2 option in Week 2 against the Chiefs if McDonald remains inactive.
report: Steelers TE Jesse James caught 3-of-5 targets for 60 yards in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Browns.

impact: James also drew a defensive holding penalty in the end zone. The 100-yard game was the first of James' career, and came in spite of Vance McDonald making his 2018 debut. James was left completely uncovered multiple times by a Chiefs defense preoccupied with stopping Antonio Brown and JuJu Smith-Schuster. Today won't be the last time that happens, but especially with McDonald now involved, James' big days are going to be too difficult to see coming to consider him an appealing TE2 streamer.
report: Jesse James caught 5-of-5 targets for 138 yards and a touchdown in the Steelers' Week 2 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: He saw a target in the first quarter, then wasn't heard from again.  Until this offense shows any signs of functional ability, Taywan will be waiver-wire material in fantasy leagues.  He played behind Tajae Sharpe in the opener.
report: Taywan Taylor went catch-less in Week 1 against the Dolphins.

impact: Taylor only saw four targets but made the most of one in particular when he shook off several tackles and ran 18 yards for Tennessee's only offensive score of the day. The team's only other touchdown came on a 66-yard direct-snap pass on fourth down from special teamers Dan Cruikshank and Kevin Byard. Taylor still isn't involved enough to consider him a weekly WR3, but his potential was certainly flashed Sunday. He's worth stashing in deeper leagues.
report: Taywan Taylor caught 3-of-4 targets for 32 yards and one touchdown in the Titans' Week 2 victory over the Texans.

impact: Taylor led the Titans in targets, but no one in this pass-catcher corps was ever going to produce on a day where Marcus Mariota and Blaine Gabbert combined for 108 passing yards.  Despite his big-play ability, Taylor has not yet put enough production or usage in the box score for Week 4 fantasy consideration against Philadelphia.
report: Taywan Taylor caught 4-of-5 targets for 30 yards in the Titans' Week 3 win over the Jaguars.

impact: This is the usage fantasy players were hoping for in the first game without Rishard Matthews. Working as the clear No. 2, Taylor was consistently involved all game, and he made perhaps the most important play of the day when he converted a fourth-and-long in overtime with a 19-yard catch along the sideline. Talented as they come and the No. 2 option in an ascending passing game, Taylor should be rostered in all formats.
report: Taywan Taylor hauled in 7-of-9 targets for 77 yards in the Titans' Week 4 win over the Eagles.

impact: Taylor flashed his big-play potential on a gain of 19, but he also cost the Titans with a first-quarter fumble that Buffalo turned into a Josh Allen rushing TD.  And that proved to be more than the difference in the game as Tennessee fell 13-12.  Taylor will be a WR5 in Week 6 against Baltimore's shutdown secondary.
report: Taywan Taylor caught 3-of-5 targets for 30 yards in the Titans' Week 5 loss to the Bills.

impact: Taylor's involvement has only gone downhill since it (coincidently) peaked a few short weeks ago, now seeing him account for just the fourth-most receiving yards on Tennessee. Despite his obvious athletic edge and explosiveness over incumbent No. 2 Tajae Sharpe, the latter was still heavily used and led the Titans in receiving (33 yards). Taylor is unfortunately only worth a stash in deeper leagues at this point.
report: Taywan Taylor hauled in his only target for a measly 13 yards in the Titans' abysmal Week 6 loss to the Ravens.

impact: Taylor had a bad drop on what would have been a 20-plus yard catch. He's been a non-factor over the last couple weeks and is behind Tajae Sharpe for targets. Taylor is just a dynasty stash.
report: Taywan Taylor one pass for eight yards in Week 7 against the Chargers.

impact: He was shut out in the first half, but was more effective after halftime, chipping in with three catches on four second-half targets. Humphries took a screen pass from Ryan Fitzpatrick 65 yards to the house late in the second quarter, but the play was called back for an illegal block by left tackle Donovan Smith. In a busy Bucs’ receiving corps, Humphries is unlikely to be a major fantasy factor next week against the Eagles.
report: Adam Humphries supplied three catches for 27 yards on five targets Sunday in the Buccaneers’ Week 1 win over the Saints.

impact: Humphries only ended up with four targets, but he made the most of them. His biggest play came on a 51-yard catch-and-run early in the third quarter. Despite that big play, Humphries is not a viable fantasy option outside of deep leagues.
report: Adam Humphries hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 82 yards in the Bucs' Week 6 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Humphries continues to work as the Bucs true WR2 in terms of snaps and routes and Sunday he was only out-targeted by Mike Evans (10) and O.J. Howard (nine). Humphries is the worst kind of player because he is not valuable for fantasy purposes on his own merit while remaining a thorn in the side of the fantasy ceilings for the members of the Tampa Bay passing game. He is not a viable fantasy option Week 8 against the Bengals.
report: Adam Humphries caught 4-of-8 targets for 37 yards in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: Evans disappointed in his matchups against Marshon Lattimore last season but he flipped the script Sunday, owning the reigning Defensive Rookie of the Year from start to finish. The Bucs stud left the field with an injury early in the second half but showed no ill effects upon his return, dusting Lattimore on a 50-yard touchdown strike from red-hot Ryan Fitzpatrick. The 147 yards were Evans’ most in a game since Week 9 of 2016 against Atlanta. He’s now just one receiving touchdown away from tying Jimmie Giles’ team record of 34. Next week’s matchup with Philadelphia won’t be an easy one, though Evans is still worthy of WR1 consideration against the reigning World Champs.
report: Mike Evans tallied seven catches for 147 yards and a touchdown on seven targets Sunday in the Buccaneers’ improbable Week 1 win over the Saints.

impact: Evans didn't get loose for vertical bombs, but he out-physicaled the Eagles' defensive backs en route to a high-volume game.  His touchdown came on an easy four-yard route where Evans simply used his big body to shield himself from beleaguered Eagles CB Jalen Mills.  The Steelers' defense has been getting torched early on, and Evans will catch them on Monday Night Football in Week 3.
report: Mike Evans caught 10-of-12 targets for 83 yards and a touchdown in the Bucs' Week 2 win over the Eagles.

impact: Unlike last week, it was DeSean Jackson (5-112) who benefited immensely as the Bucs trailed 38-3 after two quarters. Evans' nine targets were still a team-high, with Adam Humphries (6-36) seeing seven. Evans has proved to be a true WR1 with Jameis Winston, who replaced Ryan Fitzpatrick at the half, under center and that should continue once the Bucs return from their Week 5 bye.
report: Mike Evans hauled in 6-of-9 targets for 59 yards in the Bucs' Week 4 loss to the Bears.

impact: It is an extremely disappointing result considering Jameis Winston threw for 395 yards and four touchdowns. That said, Evans did not make any glaring mistakes or play poorly. He just did not really get the opportunities. That should change next week against the Browns.
report: Mike Evans hauled in 4-of-5 targets for 58 yards in the Bucs' Week 6 loss to the Falcons.

impact: After two slow weeks with 107 yards combined through the air, Evans led the Bucs across the board in receiving on Sunday. With Denzel Ward following DeSean Jackson, Evans worked mostly on Damarious Randall on the afternoon. After scoring a touchdown in each of the opening three weeks of the season, Evans has failed to reach the end zone over the past three games. Despite that, he remains a high-end WR1 option in Week 8 on the road against the Bengals.
report: Mike Evans caught 7-of-10 targets for 107 yards in Sunday's Week 7 win over the Browns.

impact: The Bucs’ backup played sparingly and was ineffective in the few instances when he was called upon, managing a long gain of just three yards. Peyton Barber served as Tampa’s workhorse in the opener, leading the Bucs’ backfield with 19 touches. We’d expect that trend to continue next week against the Eagles.
report: Jacquizz Rodgers rushed twice for only one yard while catching his lone target for a two-yard gain Sunday in the Buccaneeers’ Week 1 win over the Saints.

impact: Gabbert was predictably bad, but the bigger story is the Titans may have to start him in Week 2 with Marcus Mariota (elbow) ailing.  The Titans host the Texans next.  We'll have a better idea of Mariota's injury on Monday.
report: Blaine Gabbert completed 11-of-22 passes for 117 yards and an interception in the Titans' Week 1 loss to Miami.

impact: Marcus Mariota (elbow) was limited in warm-ups and is still struggling to grip the football. There is no official word from the Titans just yet, but it sounds like Gabbert will be starting behind a makeshift offensive line missing both starting tackles.
report: ESPN's Adam Schefter reports it's "looking more" like Blaine Gabbert will start in Week 2 against the Texans.

impact: Both Gabbert and Marcus Mariota (elbow) warmed up for the Titans' Week 2 division bout against the Texans, but it was the former who took all reps with the first-string offense. The Titans only have two available quarterbacks, so Mariota could still stay glued to the sidelines despite being active. There has been no official announcement on Tennessee's starter.
report: Blaine Gabbert is warming up with the Titans' first string offense.

impact: Marcus Mariota (elbow) is active but may only be used in an emergency. The Titans will notably be without tackles Jack Conklin, Taylor Lewan, and second-stringer Dennis Kelly against the Texans' daunting pass rush.
report: Blaine Gabbert will start in Week 2 against the Texans.

impact: Gabbert barely cracked the century mark in his spot-start for Marcus Mariota (elbow), tossing for 117 yards and an abysmal 5.8 YPA. Gabbert's fantasy production typically derives (and hinges on) his legs, but he mustered only two scrambles for two yards in Tennessee's Week 2 win. Corey Davis (5-55) still managed to lead all Titans skill players with a team-high seven targets, so consider him the focal point of Tennessee's passing game no matter who is under center moving forward.
report: Blaine Gabbert completed 13-of-20 passes for 117 yards and one touchdown in the Titans' Week 2 win over the Texans.

impact: The Titans are "hoping" Marcus Mariota (elbow) can "grip the football as soon as possible", which is a vague timeline that leaves his return wide open. Blaine Gabbert is expected to make his second consecutive start in the interim. Gabbert completed 13-of-20 passes for 117 yards and one score against the Texans in Week 2 and, if looking for a positive note, will have LT Taylor Lewan (concussion) back protecting his blindside. Although they'll be on the field for nearly every offensive play, WR Corey Davis and TE Jonnu Smith can be promptly downgraded until Mariota returns.
report: Titans QB Blaine Gabbert is expected to start in Week 3 against the Jaguars.

impact: Gabbert took a first-quarter hit so massive that he was noticeably woozy and eventually left the field with trainers.  Marcus Mariota, dealing with a nerve problem in his throwing-arm elbow, has taken over at quarterback against Jacksonville.
report: Blaine Gabbert left Sunday's Week 3 game with a concussion.

impact: Smith-Schuster won in the slot often when faced off against Briean Boddy-Calhoun with the highlight of his day being a 67-yard catch and run that set up a Steelers touchdown in the 3rd quarter. Building off an impressive rookie season, Smith-Schuster will be a starting option next week at home versus the Chiefs.
report: Steelers WR JuJu Smith-Schuster caught 5-of-8 targets for 119 yards in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Browns.

impact: With Antonio Brown gutting out a calf injury, Smith-Schuster set new career highs in both targets and catches. He benefitted from the Steelers spending literally the entire game in comeback mode. Smith-Schuster's touchdown was a two-yarder where he displayed ridiculously strong hands while getting tackled in tight coverage. He drew another end zone target later in the game but could not hook up with Ben Roethlisberger. The Steelers' No. 2 wideout is now sitting at 18/240/1 through two games. He's flirting with every-week WR1 value.
report: JuJu Smith-Schuster caught 13-of-19 targets for 121 yards and a touchdown in the Steelers' Week 2 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: With Ben Roethlisberger (successfully) fixated on getting Antonio Brown going, Smith-Schuster had his quietest game of the season. Thankfully for fantasy owners, it included a touchdown. With just eight catches over his past two games, Smith-Schuster will look to get cooking again in Week 6 against the Bengals.
report: JuJu Smith-Schuster caught 4-of-4 targets for 34 yards and a touchdown in the Steelers' Week 5 win over the Falcons.

impact: His 10 targets led the team.  JuJu made an incredible catch over the top of CB Darqueze Dennard at the goal line and was ruled down at the one, setting up a second one-yard touchdown for James Conner.  This was Smith-Schuster's fourth 100-yard game of the season as the Steelers head into their bye before hosting the Browns in Week 8.  JuJu went 5-119 in Week 1 vs. Cleveland.
report: JuJu Smith-Schuster caught 7-of-10 targets for 111 yards in the Steelers' Week 6 win over the Bengals.

impact: After a massive opening week to the season, Cook fell back in line with his career output, but was still tied for second on the team in targets. Catching 13-of-16 targets to open the season, Cook will remain a fringe TE1 entering Week 3 versus the Dolphins.
report: Jared Cook caught 4-of-4 targets for 49 yards in Sunday's Week 2 loss to the Broncos.

impact: Cook appeared to find the end zone for his first touchdown of the season in the third quarter, but replay review revealed he was down at the one. Cook has been the Raiders' only consistent pass catcher, notching at least four receptions every week out. He is proving to be a legitimate TE1 in his age-31 season.
report: Jared Cook caught 5-of-6 targets for 31 yards in the Raiders' Week 3 loss to the Dolphins.

impact: Cook dropped at least two targets, but he atoned with twin seven-yard scores and several chunk gains between the twenties.  Through four games, Cook leads the Raiders in every meaningful receiving category and has easily been the team's most-consistent pass catcher.  Cook has solidified himself as an every-week fantasy TE1 and will remain so in Week 5 against the Chargers.
report: Jared Cook caught 8-of-13 targets for 110 yards and two touchdowns in the Raiders' Week 4 win over Cleveland.

impact: Cooks' six targets on the day were still encouraging despite the results. It was always plausible this day would come given his history in boom-bust performances, too. Having said that, Cook again dropped another potential touchdown inside the 10-yard line. Given the landscape (a.k.a. wasteland) of tight ends in 2018, Cook remains a weekly matchup-proof TE1.
report: Jared Cook caught 4-of-6 targets for 20 yards in the Raiders' Week 5 loss to the Chargers.

impact: We're going to get outcomes like this when Derek Carr has no time to throw and is unwilling to make difficult throws, and both scenarios played out against the Seahawks.  Cook will enter the Raiders' Week 7 bye coming off two slow games.  He remains a huge part of the passing offense as an every-week TE1.
report: Jared Cook caught 2-of-2 targets for 10 yards in the Raiders' Week 6 loss to Seattle.

impact: Treadwell dropped his first target of the day on a third down, earning boos from the home crowd.  But he later answered with a nice 16-yard grab where he picked up some YAC and ran through an arm tackle.  Treadwell is unlikely to have any fantasy appeal unless Adam Thielen or Stefon Diggs gets hurt.
report: Laquon Treadwell caught 2-of-4 targets for 18 yards in the Vikings' Week 1 win over the 49ers.

impact: The day started out well for Treadwell, who caught the first touchdown of his career -- really -- in the first quarter. It was downhill from there, however. He dropped what would have been a third-down conversion in the third quarter, and he almost sabotaged the comeback attempt by letting a pass go right through his hands and into a DB's in the fourth quarter. He also ran the wrong route and dropped another pass in overtime. It would not be surprising if his playing time is scaled back moving forward.
report: Laquon Treadwell hauled in 2-of-6 targets for 23 yards and a touchdown in the Vikings' Week 2 tie with the Packers.

impact: Still reeling from hauling in his first career touchdown in Week 2, Treadwell reverted back to being the Vikings' fourth option in their passing game. Had Minnesota not been trailing 27-0 to start the second half, it's a wonder whether he would have even been asked to play all that much. With Adam Thielen (14-105 Sunday), Kyle Rudolph (5-48-1), and Stefon Diggs (4-17) locked into primary roles, Treadwell's good weeks will be far and few between.
report: Laquon Treadwell hauled in all four of his targets for 33 yards in the Vikings' Week 3 loss to the Bills.

impact: Diggs beat Richard Sherman for a nice gain on his first catch of the day and then bested Ahkello Witherspoon for a 22-yard touchdown on a perfectly-placed ball by Kirk Cousins down the left sideline.  It was put only where Diggs could catch it.  Diggs' day was pretty quiet after the early second-quarter score.  Diggs will be on the WR1/2 borderline next week in Green Bay.
report: Stefon Diggs caught 3-of-6 targets for 43 yards and one touchdown in the Vikings' Week 1 win over the 49ers.

impact: Diggs already was having a fine fantasy day heading into the fourth quarter after converting a well-designed play at the goal line into his second touchdown of the season, but he did not settle for fine. With the Vikings trailing in the fourth, Diggs got loose down the field, and Kirk Cousins hit him with a beautiful pass for a 75-yard touchdown. He also absolutely worked the corner to get wide open on the game-tying two-point conversion late in the fourth quarter, and he added three more catches in overtime. Up to three scores on 19 targets through two games, Diggs will be a locked-in WR1 next week against the Bills.
report: Stefon Diggs hauled in 9-of-13 targets for 128 yards and two touchdowns in the Vikings' Week 2 tie with the Packers.

impact: Unlike teammates Adam Thielen (14-105) and Kyle Rudolph (5-48-1), Diggs was unable to benefit from the Vikings' second-half blitzkrieg following their 27-0 first half deficit. He's seen 29 targets through three games, highlighted by his Week 2 overtime performance (9-128-2) against the Packers. Kirk Cousins was unable to keep his eyes downfield as the Bills' defensive line completely surprised and crushed Minnesota's pass protection throughout the afternoon. There are better days ahead for Diggs, including more top-ten scoring weeks, as long as he stays healthy.
report: Stefon Diggs caught 4-of-10 targets for 17 yards in the Vikings' Week 3 loss to the Bills.

impact: The 10-catch game was Diggs' second straight, while he's now drawn 10 targets in four straight games after a disappointing Week 1. He's cleared 90 yards in 3-of-5 contests. It has been Adam Thielen making the splash plays in the Vikings' receiver corps thus far, but it is only a matter of time before Diggs has a true blow-up game. He has stayed healthy and is seeing the requisite volume. The Vikings host the bottom-three Cardinals in Week 6.
report: Stefon Diggs caught 10-of-11 targets for 91 yards in the Vikings' Week 5 win over the Eagles, adding two carries for 25 additional yards.

impact: Diggs took a backseat to Adam Thielen, who accounted for over half of Kirk Cousins' yards. The five targets were the lowest he's seen all year. Diggs should rebound in a matchup with the Jets in Week 7.
report: Stefon Diggs caught 3-of-5 passes for 33 yards in Week 6 against the Cardinals.

impact: Adam Thielen hung a 9-110-1 day up on 10 targets while Diggs struggled in Morris Claiborne's coverage much of the afternoon.  Diggs was getting targets close to the line of scrimmage and had trouble getting anything after the catch.  The 14 targets were his second-most of the season.  Diggs will look to get back on track next week in a home game against the Saints.  The last time he saw them, in the playoffs, Diggs became a legend with the Minnesota Miracle.
report: Stefon Diggs caught 8-of-14 targets for 33 yards in the Vikings' Week 7 win over the Jets.

impact: Bibbs was the Redskins' No. 2/change of pace with Chris Thompson sidelined. Thompson seemed close to suiting up this week, so Bibbs is not a compelling waiver wire add.
report: Kapri Bibbs rushed twice for 11 yards in the Redskins' Week 6 win over the Panthers, adding a six-yard reception.

impact: Without Chris Thompson for the second straight week, Bibbs again stepped in as Washington's No. 2 change-of-pace back. He showed his worth on Washington's first drive when he stretched a screen in the flats into a 23-yard touchdown scamper. His 43 receiving yards tied Jordan Reed's for the team lead. Bibbs has been out-carried by Adrian Peterson 41-4 over the last two games, though, and would need more consistent usage to be deemed a potential streamer moving forward. He's worthy of stashing in the event both Peterson and Thompson are ruled out later on.
report: Kapri Bibbs rushed two times for 16 yards, adding four catches for 43 yards and one touchdown through the air in the Redskins' Week 7 win over the Cowboys.

impact: After losing Amari Cooper (concussion), the Raiders are down to Jordy Nelson, Martavis Bryant, and Dwayne Harris at wide receiver.  Roberts immediately went to the locker room after suffering his fourth-quarter brain injury.  The slot receiver had five catches for 31 yards on six targets before departing.
report: Raiders WR Seth Roberts left Sunday's Week 6 game with a concussion.

impact: Dalvin Cook played every snap of the first two series before Murray opened the third series and then handled much of the clock-killing work in the fourth quarter.  Neither back found the end zone, while Murray wasn't targeted in the pass game.  Murray is little more than a handcuff to Cook owners.
report: Latavius Murray rushed 11 times for 42 yards in the Vikings' Week 1 win over the 49ers.

impact: Murray was stuck on two carries before Dalvin Cook left with a hamstring injury in overtime. That issue is reportedly minor -- Cook described it as a cramp -- but it is enough to keep Murray on fantasy rosters for now. That said, he is nothing more than a handcuff.
report: Latavius Murray rushed four times for 19 yards in the Vikings' Week 2 tie with the Packers.

impact: Oof. What initially appeared to be the perfect game script situation for Murray turned out to be an absolute nightmare for the Vikings' offense. Minnesota's offensive line was a travesty throughout the afternoon, allowing Kirk Cousins to be blindsided and fumble on the team's first two offensive possessions. By the time the Vikings got the ball back for their third possession, they were already staring down the barrel of a 17-0 deficit. Minnesota's backfield received a paltry four carries on the day, totaling 12 rushing yards (3.0 YPC). Murray's five catches fortunately salvaged what could've been an even bigger disaster of an outing. Dalvin Cook is expected to return on Thursday against the Rams.
report: Latavius Murray rushed two times for one yard and added five catches for 30 receiving yards in the Vikings' Week 3 loss to the Bills.

impact: It was yet another disappointing affair for a player who is now averaging 3.53 yards per carry. Ominously, Murray ceded both a red zone target and goal line carry to "Roc Thomas." If Dalvin Cook (hamstring) can ever get healthy, Murray might have a hard time carving out a role. For now, Cook seems unlikely to play in Week 6, leaving Murray in the desperation FLEX mix against the Cardinals.
report: Latavius Murray rushed 11 times for 42 yards in the Vikings' Week 5 win over the Eagles, adding two receptions for 14 additional yards.

impact: With Dalvin Cook out, Murray rebounded from his disappointing Week 5. He ripped the Cardinals for three 20-plus yard runs, with his touchdown coming on a highlight 21-yarder where he stiff-armed into the end-zone. Murray came into Sunday averaging just 3.5 YPC, but he made a case for a role when Dalvin Cook returns. Cook would be a plug-and-play RB2 if Cook isn't back for Week 7.
report: Latavius Murray rushed 24 times for 155 yards and a touchdown in the Vikings' Week 6 win over the Cardinals.

impact: He added two catches for 14 yards on a pair of targets.  Murray's first score was an 11-yard scamper up the middle, and the second was an untouched run through the left side from 38 yards away.  With Dalvin Cook still struggling to get healthy, Murray has emerged as a strong RB2 with reliable workloads.  If Cook sits again, Murray will again be in play Week 8 against the Saints.
report: Latavius Murray rushed 15 times for 69 yards and two touchdowns in the Vikings' Week 7 win over the Jets.

impact: Conner had one blip on his resume with a fumble in the 4th quarter that let the Browns back in the game, but other than that, had a dominant game as a dual purpose back. Conner had an untouched 4-yard rushing score in the 2nd quarter and then a 22-yard touchdown run in the 3rd quarter. On top of his performance, no other Steeler RB even registered a touch in the game. As long as Le'Veon Bell continues his hold out, Conner is a RB1 for fantasy purposes.
report: Steelers RB James Conner rushed 31 times for 135 yards and two touchdowns while catching 5-of-6 targets for 57 yards in Sunday's Week 1 game versus the Browns.

impact: With the Steelers down 21-0 by the end of the first quarter, they never bothered to establish the run. Conner missed some time with an injury, but the Steelers never announced what was bothering him. Stevan Ridley ran in his place. Conner was on the field to finish the game. Provided Le'Veon Bell does not report this week, Conner will again be a usage-based RB1 for Week 3 against the Bucs.
report: James Conner rushed eight times for 17 yards and a touchdown in the Steelers' Week 2 loss to the Chiefs, adding five receptions for 48 additional yards.

impact: Conner fell victim to gameflow with the Ravens winning time of possesion. The Steelers went pass-heavy after getting behind early and didn't have any red-zone trips. Conner managed to catch a two-point conversion to save his night, but it was still his worst game to date. Conner will be an RB2 for Week 5 against the Falcons.
report: James Conner rushed nine times for 19 yards and caught 3-of-7 targets for 25 yards in Week 4 against the Ravens.

impact: Conner touched the ball seven times for 72 yards and a score on the opening drive and never looked back. He was piling on yards after first contact against the Falcons' injury-ruined defense. Conner has now hit 185 yards from scrimmage in 2-of-5 games, though he's totaled just 204 yards across his other three contests. Thankfully for his fantasy owners, the Bengals are an attackable Week 6 matchup. The Steelers then go on bye in Week 7. That is when Le'Veon Bell is expected to finally return.
report: James Conner rushed 21 times for 110 yards and two touchdowns in the Steelers' Week 5 win over the Falcons, adding four receptions for 75 additional yards.

impact: He added four catches for 18 yards on seven targets.  The NFL's leading tackle-shedder, Conner showed it in this one, consistently bulldozing would-be tacklers and injuring a couple along the way as S Shawn Williams was concussed on one of the long runs.  Conner's scores were both of the one-yard plunge variety.  He should have had a third touchdown but was ruled down at the one before getting stuffed on 1st- and 3rd-and-goal runs.  A premier RB1, Conner's workload will now be subject to question with Le'Veon Bell expected to report to the team during the Week 7 bye.
report: James Conner rushed 19 times for 111 yards and two touchdowns in the Steelers' 28-21, Week 6 win over the Bengals.

impact: He led the team in targets, just ahead of Nelson Agholor (12).  Ertz has been the Eagles' most-targeted pass catcher with Nick Foles under center dating back to last season.  Carson Wentz (knee) is tentatively due back for Week 3 against the Colts, however, and Wentz's return would boost Ertz's touchdown probability.  Ertz has yet to reach pay dirt on 23 targets through two games.
report: Zach Ertz caught 11-of-13 targets for 94 yards in the Eagles' Week 2 loss to Tampa Bay.

impact: Ertz and Wentz more than less picked up where they left off as Ertz lead the Eagles across the board in targets, receptions and yards. Despite failing to score through three games, Ertz leads the Eagles in targets (33), receptions (21) and receiving yardage (215). He will be a set-and-forget option next week against the Titans.
report: Zach Ertz caught 5-of-10 targets for 73 yards in Sunday's Week 3 win over the Colts.

impact: It is about what we have come to expect from Ertz, who now has at least 10 targets in every game this season. The Titans simply had no answer for him as he consistently made plays across the middle on the way to his first 100-yard game of the season. With Wentz looking better every week, Ertz will remain a high-end TE1 as long as he is healthy.
report: Zach Ertz hauled in 10-of-14 targets for 112 yards in the Eagles' Week 4 loss to the Titans.

impact: Ertz has now caught 10 passes in 3-of-5 games this season. He's on pace for 1,398 yards after entering 2018 with a career high of 853. His production has come with both Nick Foles and Carson Wentz under center and withstood the return of Alshon Jeffery. Ertz will jockey with Rob Gronkowski and Travis Kelce for the TE1 rank going forward.
report: Zach Ertz caught 10-of-11 targets for 110 yards and a touchdown in the Eagles' Week 5 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Ertz was legitimately unstoppable, relentlessly beating the Panthers’ linebackers and safeties on slants and exploiting every hole known to man in Carolina’s zone coverage. Ertz came oh-so close to a second-quarter touchdown, but he was tackled just short of the goalline.  As the NFL’s premier route-running tight end, Ertz has also been fantasy football’s most-consistent TE1. Even against the Jaguars in London in Week 8, Ertz will be a top-three option at the position at worst.
report: Zach Ertz caught 9-of-11 targets for 138 yards in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to the Panthers.

impact: His longest catch went for 21 yards. Three of Watson’s four grabs came after halftime as the Saints did their best to chip away at a 24-point deficit. The veteran carries mild streaming appeal as a proven pass-catcher in a high-scoring attack, though most weeks, the Saints will run their offense through Michael Thomas and Alvin Kamara.
report: Ben Watson corralled all four of his targets for 44 yards Sunday in New Orleans’ Week 1 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: Watson's overall line was a disappointment, but he had a wide open touchdown opportunity in the first quarter in which he was overthrown. Through two games, Watson has just nine catches for 63 yards and is only a desperation TE2 option in Week 3 versus the Falcons.
report: Ben Watson caught 3-of-5 targets for 19 yards in Sunday's Week 2 win over the Browns.

impact: Watson made a number of contested catches including a 19-yard grab that set up a Saints field goal late in the first half. Even at his advanced age, Watson remains a physical presence and a tough matchup for opposing defenses. Still, with so many mouths to feed in New Orleans, he’s best viewed as a TE2 for fantasy purposes.
report: Benjamin Watson nabbed five-of-six targets for 71 yards Sunday in New Orleans’ Week 3 win over the Falcons.

impact: Watson dropped a seven-yard touchdown on one of his missed connections, and the Saints had to settle for one of their four first-half field goals.  It was a step back for Watson in a glorious spot.  He'll be a fringe TE1/2 next week when the Saints go back home to face the Redskins at the Superdome.
report: Ben Watson caught 1-of-3 targets for 23 yards in the Saints' Week 4 win over the Giants.

impact: Both the grabs and targets were Watson's most of the season. The score was his first of the year. Watson is averaging just 38 weekly yards, but that is more than enough to make him a weekly TE2 in a down campaign for the position.
report: Ben Watson caught 6-of-6 targets for 43 yards and a touchdown in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens.

impact: Filling in for Austin Seferian-Jenkins, who appeared to aggravate his core-muscle injury, Paul racked up five of his catches in the second half. If ASJ is forced to miss time, Paul would get into the TE2 conversation at a desolate position.
report: Niles Paul hauled in 7-of-9 targets for 65 yards in the Jaguars' Week 5 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Backfield mate Marshawn Lynch handled just nine carries since the game was out of hand early. Richard was involved late, finishing second on the team in receiving yards. Richard has shown a propensity to produce when involved — the issue being he's never involved. If Lynch ever misses time, there's no doubt Richard will sneak into strong RB3/FLEX consideration.
report: Jalen Richard caught all six of his targets for 53 yards and one touchdown in the Raiders' Week 5 stomping to the Chargers.

impact: When the Raiders play from behind, Richard's usage spikes as a frequent checkdown target for checkdown-loving Derek Carr.  The team's leading receiver in Sunday's blowout loss, Richard will remain a negative-game-script-dependent, PPR-only flex option when Oakland emerges from its Week 7 bye.
report: Jalen Richard caught 7-of-8 targets for 48 yards and rushed twice for three yards in the Raiders' Week 6 loss to Seattle.

impact: Sharing time with Jalen Richard as the Raiders' backups to Marshawn Lynch, Martin is worth rostering in fantasy leagues only as a deep-league handcuff/stash.
report: Doug Martin managed 11 yards on five carries in the Raiders' Week 4 win.

impact: He was quickly ruled out for the rest of the game.  Wallace caught one pass for no gain and appeared to suffer a potentially severe injury on the play.  Wallace had a towel over his head and appeared distraught as he made his way on the cart to the locker room.  The Eagles are already without Alshon Jeffery (shoulder) and Mack Hollins (groin, I.R.).  They're down to Nelson Agholor, DeAndre Carter, Shelton Gibson, and Kamar Aiken at wideout.
report: Mike Wallace was carted off in the first quarter of Sunday's Week 2 game with an ankle injury.

impact: Cole got off to a great start with a 31-yard catch on the second play of the game, but he was mostly quiet as Blake Bortles struggled the rest of the way. He did lead the Jaguars with 54 yards, but Dede Westbrook paced the receivers with 6 targets. Cole will remain an upside WR4 play next week against the Patriots.
report: Keelan Cole hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 54 yards in the Jaguars' Week 1 win over the Giants.

impact: After a quiet Week 1, Cole delivered on his summer hype, giving him three 100-yard games over his past five regular season contests. The highlights were in the first quarter, where Cole made a one-handed, Odell Beckham-esque 22-yard catch on Eric Rowe down the sideline. He finished the job by dismantling Rowe for a 24-yard score three plays later. Cole is simply a born playmaker down the field. The Jags' receiver rotation will make him uneven in fantasy, but he's earned the right to be treated as an every-week WR3.
report: Keelan Cole caught 7-of-8 targets for 116 yards and a touchdown in the Jaguars' Week 2 win over the Patriots.

impact: Cole led the Jags in targets, but Blake Bortles' wild inaccuracies returned, and Jacksonville got nothing going in the downfield passing game.  Cole has an abundance of talent, but this offense is simply not worthy of trust for him to be viewed as anything more than a volatile WR3/flex option in Week 4 versus the Jets.
report: Keelan Cole caught 5-of-9 targets for 40 yards in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to Tennessee.

impact: It was a quiet game for Cole with Dede Westbrook and Donte Moncrief both going over 100 yards. Cole made both of his catches in the first quarter and was a non-factor in the second half. He's now been held under 40 yards in back to back games. The Jagaurs spread it out offense is going to be dificult to predict on a week to week basis. Cole will just be a low-end WR3 for Week 5.
report: Keelan Cole caught 2-of-3 passes for 15 yards in Week 4 against the Jets.

impact: Cole played a big role in the Jaguars' only good drive of the game, hauling in a 32-yard pass to help set up a touchdown on the next play. He also drew a deep target at the end of the first half, but it was a non-descript game for Jacksonville's 1A receiver. He will be just a WR4 play next week in Dallas.
report: Keelan Cole hauled in 4-of-10 targets for 70 yards in the Jaguars' Week 5 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Three of his grabs came with Jacksonville down big in the second half. Cole was stripped by Jaylen Smith in the third quarter, resulting in a turnover. It's been a quiet stretch for the second-year wideout, who has topped 50 yards just once during his current four-game touchdown drought. Cole is just a bench stash at this point.
report: Keelan Cole collected four catches for 41 yards on five targets Sunday in the Jags’ Week 6 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: It was an inefficient day for Cole as the Jaguars benched Blake Bortles and turned to game-manager backup Cody Kessler for 30 second-half pass attempts. Even in a favorable matchup, Cole will be a low-floor WR4 option as the Jaguars head to London for Week 8 to face the Eagles.
report: Keelan Cole caught 2-of-7 targets for 21 yards in the Jaguars’ Week 7 loss to the Texans.

impact: It was an improvement on the four touches Montgomery saw in Week 1, but he still has been mostly uninvolved through two weeks. More worryingly, Aaron Jones is due back from suspension in Week 3. Montgomery is not a must-roster player in standard scoring.
report: Ty Montgomery rushed five times for 31 yards and caught 1-of-2 targets for nine yards in the Packers' Week 2 tie with the Vikings.

impact: With Aaron Rodgers' receivers struggling to make big plays, TyMont finally got involved as a pass catcher/outlet. Both his 10 touches and 64 yards led the Packers' three-man backfield. Especially with Randall Cobb struggling, the Pack figure to work on getting Montgomery more involved on a weekly basis. The Bills are an appetizing Week 4 matchup.
report: Ty Montgomery caught 6-of-7 targets for 48 yards in the Packers' Week 3 loss to the Redskins, adding four carries for 16 additional yards.

impact: Most of Montgomery's yardage came when he got a free release down the left sideline for a 43-yard catch in the first quarter. The Pack's backfield remained a three-man rotation this afternoon, with Aaron Jones winning both the touch and yardage battles. Montgomery will continue to struggle for value outside of PPR leagues.
report: Ty Montgomery caught 2-of-3 targets for 56 yards in the Packers' Week 4 win over the Bills, adding five rushes for 18 additional yards.

impact: Montgomery got a ton of playing time in the second half with the Packers in catchup mode.  He has no fantasy value outside of deeper PPR leagues.
report: Ty Montgomery rushed four times for 15 yards in the Packers' Week 5 loss to the Lions, adding a 23-yard catch on three targets.

impact: Higgins led Cleveland in receiving yards in a game where Baker Mayfield spread the ball around.  David Njoku's five catches led the team.  Higgins has a secure role in three-receiver sets alongside Jarvis Landry and Antonio Callaway but lacks fantasy value outside of Dynasty leagues.
report: Rashard Higgins caught 4-of-5 targets for 61 yards in the Browns' Week 4 loss to the Raiders.

impact: Higgins was having a productive day, catching 3-of-4 targets for 66 yards and a touchdown. His 19-yard touchdown before the first half put the Browns up 6-3 at the half.
report: Rishard Higgins suffered a knee injury in Sunday's Week 5 game versus the Ravens and his return is doubtful.

impact: It was a balanced effort for Thomas, who recorded exactly eight catches for 90 yards in both halves. Thomas capped the second quarter with a six-yard touchdown grab on a play where the Bucs left him completely open. He nearly scored again in the fourth quarter, but was stopped just short of the goal line. Even at full strength the Bucs would have had a hard time defending Thomas, but with Brent Grimes (groin) out and Vernon Hargreaves exiting in the second half, Tampa Bay’s weakened secondary didn’t have a prayer. The third-year stud should stuff the stat sheet again in next week’s home matchup against the Browns.
report: Michael Thomas delivered a team-record 16 catches for 180 yards and a touchdown on 17 targets Sunday in the Saints’ Week 1 loss to the Buccaneers.

impact: Thomas did lose a fumble for the second straight game, but that was his only blemish on a nearly perfect day. Thomas scored both of the Saints' touchdowns, catching a 2-yard score in the third quarter to pull the Saints within a score and then catching a 5-yard touchdown over Denzel Ward to give New Orleans a lead with 2:40 left in the fourth quarter. Thomas now has reeled in 28 receptions through two weeks, which is the most for any player through two weeks in NFL history. Thomas will be a set and forget WR1 option next week when the Saints head to Atlanta.
report: Michael Thomas caught 12-of-13 targets for 89 yards and two touchdowns in Sunday's Week 2 win over the Browns.

impact: Thomas set the tone with a 35-yard gain on the Saints’ first play from scrimmage. He never managed to find the end zone but was always there when Drew Brees needed him. Thomas played a pivotal role in overtime, moving the chains with three catches for 38 yards on the game-clinching drive. Sunday’s 10-spot gives Thomas 38 catches for the year, an NFL record through the first three games. He’s also been incredibly efficient, absorbing an impossible 95 percent of his targets this year. Even with Janoris Jenkins likely to shadow him in Week 4, the red-hot Thomas will remain an appealing WR1 against the Giants.
report: Michael Thomas pulled in all 10 of his targets for 129 receiving yards Sunday in the Saints’ Week 3 victory over Atlanta.

impact: Thomas tallied at least 10 catches and/or one touchdown in each of the first three games entering Sunday.  His four targets were tied with Cameron Meredith for second on the team behind Alvin Kamara's nine, and Drew Brees didn't throw a single touchdown as Kamara rushed for three.  Thomas should bounce back no problem back at home against the Redskins in Week 5.
report: Michael Thomas caught all four of his targets for 47 yards in the Saints' Week 4 win over the Giants.

impact: After seeing 40 combined targets Weeks 1-3, Thomas has been targeted a total of nine times the past two weeks and hasn't scored in either game.  He was obviously never going to continue at that ridiculous three-week pace, but there are so many talented players in this offense with the emergence of Tre'Quan Smith (3-111-2 tonight) and return of Mark Ingram that the Saints can spread the ball around.  Thomas will get a difficult matchup on the road against the Ravens in Week 7 when the Saints come off their bye.
report: Michael Thomas caught 4-of-5 targets for 74 yards in the Saints' Week 5 win over the Redskins.

impact: The catches were Thomas' most since Week 3, while the score was his first since Week 2. Surprisingly, Thomas has failed to clear 10 targets or 75 yards in each of his past three games. He has a tough Week 8 matchup in Xavier Rhodes and the Vikings, though Rhodes could end up missing the game with an ankle injury.
report: Michael Thomas caught 7-of-9 targets for 69 yards and a touchdown in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens.

impact: Even with Leonard Fournette leaving with an injury, Grant did not see much action against the Giants. Perhaps that changes if Fournette is forced to miss time, but T.J. Yeldon is the back to add.
report: Corey Grant rushed once for three yards in the Jaguars' Week 1 win over the Giants.

impact: Grant ended up forming a near-even committee with T.J. Yeldon in Leonard Fournette's absence. The Jags worked hard to exploit Grant's play-making ability as a pass catcher. He was a spark plug who picked up a number of key first downs. Despite his big-play ability, Grant will be a low-end RB3/FLEX if Fournette remains sidelined for Week 3 against the Titans.
report: Corey Grant caught 6-of-7 targets for 56 yards in the Jaguars' Week 2 win over the Patriots, adding four rushes for 13 additional yards.

impact: Grant started the game in place of Leonard Fournette (hamstring), but the Jags wound up going with T.J. Yeldon because Grant was so ineffective.  Grant was barely even seen in the second half, while Yeldon finished with 13 touches to Grant's 7.  All in all, it was an abysmal offensive effort from a Jaguars team that played so well versus New England the week prior.  Fournette was close to playing and figures to return in Week 4 against the Jets.
report: Corey Grant rushed six times for 11 yards and caught 1-of-2 targets for a combined loss of one yard in the Jaguars' Week 3 loss to Tennessee.

impact: Grant had his lower leg caught underneath a tackler at the end of a second-quarter run. He was not able to put weight on his left leg as he was helped off the field, and he was pretty quickly ruled out. With Leonard Fournette inactive, T.J. Yeldon should get as much work as he can handle against the Chiefs. Brandon Wilds is Jacksonville's other active running back.
report: Corey Grant exited Week 5 against the Chiefs with a foot injury.

impact: Grant had to be carted off the field Sunday.  He was hyped up over the summer as someone the Jaguars wanted to get more involved in the offense, but it never really happened as Grant got 13 carries and turned them into 40 scoreless yards.  Grant nabbed nine catches for 67 yards.  He'll be a 27-year-old free agent next March coming off one of the most serious foot injuries.
report: ESPN's Adam Schefter reports Corey Grant suffered a Lisfranc injury Week 5 against the Chiefs and is expected to miss the remainder of the season.

impact: The second-year UDFA was sprung into extra snaps with Marquise Goodwin and Dante Pettis both leaving the game with leg injuries. Bourne was able to convert the extra looks into a two-yard touchdown for his second touchdown of the year. He will return to his backup role once Goodwin and Pettis return to action.
report: Kendrick Bourne caught 3-of-4 targets for 34 yards and a touchdown in the 49ers' Week 4 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Making his 2018 debut after serving a four-game suspension to open the season, Ingram got the start and out-touched Alvin Kamara 18-9, adding two catches for 20 yards on three targets.  It was evident right from the get-go that coach Sean Payton wanted to get Ingram involved and keep him involved after sitting out the first four weeks.  It was also an opportunity for Kamara to get some extra rest heading into the bye.  Moving forward, we expect Kamara to be used much more than he was tonight, but there's obviously some serious concern here with all the weapons and mouths in the New Orleans offense.  Kamara is unlikely to match his 22.75 touches per game mark from Weeks 1-4.  He's going to need big plays to maintain elite RB1 status while Ingram is very much a mid-to-high RB2 the rest of the way.  The Saints get the Ravens on the road in Week 7.
report: Mark Ingram rushed 16 times for 53 yards and two touchdowns in the Saints' 43-19, Week 5 rout of the Redskins on Monday night.

impact: Ingram out-touched Kamara 18-9 in his Week 5 debut, but Kamara had a 19-14 upper hand in Baltimore. Ingram received carries from the Ravens' six- and five-yard line but could not cash either in. Kamara found the end zone from two yards out in the fourth quarter. This is more how we were expecting the Saints' backfield to look following Ingram's return but nothing is settled after only two games. Ingram will be a touchdown-dependent RB2 for Week 8 against the Vikings.
report: Mark Ingram rushed 12 times for 32 scoreless yards in the Saints' Week 7 win over the Ravens, adding two catches for 10 additional yards.

impact: Smallwood's usage increased because Jay Ajayi missed almost the entire first half and Darren Sproles (hamstring) was out.  Unfortunately, Smallwood lost a fumble and Ajayi returned.  Smallwood shouldn't have a Week 3 role versus the Colts.
report: Wendell Smallwood rushed seven times for 28 yards and caught his lone target for a gain of two in the Eagles' Week 2 loss to Tampa Bay.

impact: Smallwood drew the start and out-gained Corey Clement despite receiving just 13 touches. His 4-yard touchdown rush with 3:02 left in the 4th quarter put the Eagles up for good. If both Jay Ajayi and Darren Sproles remained sidelined in Week 4, Smallwood will be in the mix as a FLEX option next week against the Titans.
report: Wendell Smallwood rushed 10 times for 56 yards and a touchdown while catching 3-of-5 targets for 35 yards in Sunday's Week 4 win over the Colts.

impact: With both Corey Clement and Darren Sproles sidelined, Smallwood served as the No. 2 back behind Jay Ajayi. It was not always pretty -- he missed a blitz pickup in the two-minute drill -- but he was able to provide a couple nice runs. With Clement's and Sproles' availability up in the air, Smallwood is worth a look in deeper leagues.
report: Wendell Smallwood rushed five times for 39 yards and hauled in 3-of-5 targets for 15 yards in the Eagles' Week 4 loss to the Titans.

impact: Corey Clement (quad) was announced as active but ended up playing zero snaps. Smallwood drew Jay Ajayi to a playing time standstill and out-gained him 71-34. He did have a first half lowlight with a red zone drop. Smallwood has shown signs of life the past three weeks but is still an uninspiring FLEX option in PPR leagues. He's a bye week "if you must" play.
report: Wendell Smallwood rushed three times for 27 yards in the Eagles' Week 5 loss to the Vikings, adding three catches for 44 additional yards and a touchdown.

impact: Smallwood’s 11 touches led the Eagles’ backfield; Corey Clement logged 10 and Josh Adams 4. Smallwood had multiple big plays nullified by penalties, including a monster screen pass of 50-plus yards that came about partly because of RG Brandon Brooks’ holding flag. Entrenched in a three-man backfield, Smallwood will be a sub-par Week 8 flex option against the Jags.
report: Wendell Smallwood rushed nine times for 32 yards and caught 2-of-2 targets for five yards in the Eagles’ Week 7 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Juszczyk was on the field for 68 of San Francisco's 98 offensive snaps. He showed well as a receiver, nabbing three catches for a team-leading 56 yards in the first half. This game was sort of a perfect storm for Juszczyk with Matt Breida (ankle) injured and the Niners playing from behind. Fullbacks have grown almost extinct in today's NFL but Juszczyk continues to play a prominent role both as a blocker and a pass-catcher. In fact, he may be the best receiving back the Niners have at the moment.
report: Kyle Juszczyk nabbed six catches for 75 yards on seven targets while adding one rush for 12 yards Sunday in San Francisco’s Week 5 loss to the Cardinals.

impact: This marks Garoppolo's first career loss after opening 7-0 as a starter.  Garoppolo tried to lead a comeback with the Vikings up by 18 deep into the third quarter, but the red-zone offense left a lot to be desired Sunday.  Garoppolo missed a wide-open George Kittle on a would-be four-yard touchdown and earlier overshot Kittle on a deep ball after he beat Harrison Smith.  Garoppolo also had a possible 80-yard TD dropped by Kittle.  His touchdown was a beautiful 22-yard hookup with rookie Dante Pettis after Garoppolo spun out of a sack.  He missed too many throws in this one, however, though it was a very tough road date with one of the league's best defenses.  The Niners will host the Lions in their home opener next Sunday.  Garoppolo will be a back-end QB1.
report: Jimmy Garoppolo completed just 15-of-33 passes for 261 yards, one touchdown, and three interceptions in the 49ers' 24-16, Week 1 loss to the Vikings.

impact: Jimmy G also took six sacks for a loss of 50 yards. Garoppolo dialed up a sideline pass to a wide-open Kendrick Bourne for his first touchdown of the day early in the second quarter. He added to his touchdown tally with another score in the third quarter, this time connecting with tight end Garrett Celek for 11 yards. Garoppolo narrowly avoided disaster in the fourth as a Tracy Walker interception was negated by a holding call on Quandre Diggs. That interception would have set the Lions up with first-and-goal and a chance to take the lead with just over two minutes remaining. As his six sacks would attest to, Garoppolo often held on to the ball too long, though all in all, Sunday was a much better performance than his last one against the Vikings in Week 1. Now 8-1 as an NFL starting quarterback, Handsome Jimmy will head to KC next week for a shootout with Patrick Mahomes and the 2-0 Chiefs.
report: Jimmy Garoppolo completed 18-of-26 passes for 206 yards and two touchdowns while contributing four yards on three carries Sunday in the 49ers’ Week 2 win over the Lions.

impact: Garoppolo decided to stay in bounds at the end of a fourth-quarter run and ended up taking a big hit on the sideline. Trainers appeared to be examining his left leg -- not his head -- on the sidelines, and that leg was extended straight out in front of him on the cart. Garoppolo had an up-and-down game before exiting, but he led the 49ers back in the second half. He finished the day with 251 yards and two scores.
report: Jimmy Garoppolo was carted to the locker room with a knee injury late in the fourth quarter Week 3 against the Chiefs.

impact: Garoppolo took a big hit along the sidelines late in the fourth quarter of San Francisco's Week 3 loss. It originally seemed like he could be dealing with a concussion, but he ended up being carted to the locker room with his left leg extended straight in front of him. If it is actually an ACL, Garoppolo will be the second offensive star the 49ers lose to an ACL tear after Jerick McKinnon suffered the same injury in the preseason. Brutal.
report: 49ers coach Kyle Shanahan said the team is "fearing" an ACL tear for Jimmy Garoppolo.

impact: Kessler replaced Blake Bortles a little after halftime following Bortles’ second lost fumble. A weak-armed game manager, Kessler engineered just one touchdown drive. Kessler’s pick came on a dropped pass, which deflected to Texans S Tyrann Mathieu. Kessler will presumably get the Week 8 start against Philadelphia in London, although he won’t be more than a low-end two-quarterback-league play.
report: Cody Kessler completed 21-of-30 passes for 156 yards, one touchdown, and one interception in the Jaguars' Week 7 loss to the Texans.

impact: One of Williams' missed connections was a dropped 39-yard touchdown in the end zone. There was no one in Williams' area code and he simply put the ball on the ground. It was a bad moment in a game full of them for the Chargers' offense. Rotating with Travis Benjamin and Mike Williams behind Keenan Allen, Williams doesn't have much of a WR5 case right now.
report: Tyrell Williams caught 2-of-5 targets for eight yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: It was a quiet game for Williams, though he improved on his eight yards for Week 1. Williams has been dealing with a groin injury, but looked fully healthy. The Chargers' deep threat remains off the fantasy radar.
report: Tyrell Williams caught three passes for 48 yards in Week 2 against Buffalo.

impact: Williams' grip as the Chargers No. 2 receiver is really loosening with Mike Williams taking a second-year leap. Mike Williams had as many touchdown grabs (2) today as Tyrell Williams had receptions. Tyrell Williams is just a deep threat for Rivers and is off the fantasy radar.
report: Tyrell Williams caught two passes for 22 yards in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: Williams had more targets than Mike Williams in a game where Travis Benjamin (foot) left in the first quarter. Tyrell can bring in an occasional long touchdown for Rivers, but his weekly floor is really low since he's averaging just four targets per game. Williams will look for his first 50+ yard game next week against the burnable Raiders.
report: Tyrell Williams caught 3-of-5 targets for 48 scoreless yards in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: None of his catches resulted in a touchdown, of course. It was the third time this season that Williams has seen just three targets, which now puts him at just 19 on the year. If searching for positives, it was his first 50-plus yard outing of the year and he did manage to finish second on the team in receiving yards. At this point, The Gazelle should only be owned in deeper leagues.
report: Tyrell Williams hauled in all three of his targets for 66 yards in the Chargers' Week 5 victory over the Raiders.

impact: Williams did all of his damage in the first half. His day got started on a two-play, 85-yard drive in which he caught a 40-yard pass over the top of the defense and then a 45-yard touchdown pass in which he took the ball from Damarious Randall on a simultaneous reception in the end zone. Williams then added a 29-yard touchdown strike with 51 seconds remaining in the first half to put the Chargers ahead 21-6 at the half. Williams entered Sunday with 192 yards and one touchdown, so he won't be an option next week when the Chargers head to London to face the Titans.
report: Tyrell Williams caught 3-of-4 targets for 118 yards and two touchdowns in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Williams roasted Logan Ryan for a 75-yard touchdown on the Chargers’ first play. He had a quiet second half with the Chargers losing the time-of-possesion battle. Williams is a one-trick deep threat, but he's had a high floor this season, with at least 40 yards or a touchdown in 6-of-7 games. Williams gets a matchup with Seattle in Week 9.
report: Tyrell Williams caught four passes for 118 yards and a touchdown in Week 7 against the Titans.

impact: Standard operating procedure for one of the league's truly elite wide receivers. Allen is so quick in and out of his breaks and spent much of the afternoon toying with the Chiefs' replacement-level defensive backs. For Week 2 he gets a Bills secondary that got ripped by the Ravens on Sunday.
report: Keenan Allen caught 8-of-11 targets for 108 yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Allen led the Chargers in receiving in a spread-it-out game from Philip Rivers. The Chargers got up big early and didn't need to pass much in the second half, so Allen didn't get a ton of chances to exploit Buffalo's secondary. Allen is averaging seven catches and 88 yards through two games. He gets a matchup with the Rams in Week 3.
report: Keenan Allen caught 6-of-8 passes for 67 yards in the Chargers' Week 2 win over Buffalo.

impact: Allen was bottled up by the Rams defense despite Marcus Peters and Aqib Talib leaving the game early with injuries. Instead it was Mike Williams -- he also had seven targets -- who did the damage for the Chargers. Near the end of the game, Allen limped over to the sideline in some pain, but it appeared to not be very serious. Assuming the injury is minor, Allen will be a WR1/2 in a home matchup against the Garoppolo-less 49ers.
report: Keenan Allen caught 3-of-7 targets for 44 yards in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: That means Keenan Allen (knee, tooth) and Travis Benjamin (foot) are officially active. The matchup for Allen is fantastic with Richard Sherman (calf) and S Jaquiski Tartt (shoulder) both inactive for the 49ers. Travis Benjamin's usage will be something to watch with Mike Williams breaking out for the Chargers. Joey Bosa (foot) is expected to be sidelined until the second half of the season.
report: Chargers declare LB Kyzir White, C Cole Toner, T Joe Barksdale, G Forrest Lamp, WR JJ Jones, DT T.Y. McGill, and DE Joey Bosa inactive for Week 4's game against the 49ers.

impact: Allen missed some practice time this week with knee and tooth soreness, but he was able to play through it. The 49ers were down two starting players in the secondary, but Allen was held in check in a game that featured Melvin Gordon. Allen is still on pace for a 96-1,128-4 season receiving line on 144 targets despite three straight average games. Look for Allen to return to low-end WR1 form against the Raiders next Sunday.
report: Keenan Allen caught 7-of-10 targets for 63 scoreless yards in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: Allen has now seen at least seven targets in every game, and at least nine in three-of-five. Although he's recorded just one touchdown on the year, his massive volume (nine targets per game) will inevitably lead to more fireworks-style outings for owners in the near future. His red zone usage has admittedly taken a hit with Melvin Gordon so heavily involved out of the backfield this year, but Allen's weekly floor still makes him one of the safest plays going in fantasy. He's on pace for a usage-hog 102-1,190-3 season, and remains a safe WR1 in Week 6 against the Browns.
report: Keenan Allen vacuumed 8-of-9 targets for 90 yards in the Chargers' Week 5 rout over the Raiders.

impact: Allen got his day started off strong with two catches for 33 yards on the opening drive of the game. The Chargers took the air out of the ball in the second half, but his rushing performance made his day a respectable one as his four carries were a career-high. In fact, for his career, Allen had just three rushes for 11 yards entering Sunday's game. Allen hasn't been the WR1 fantasy owners drafted to begin the season, but got off to a slow statistical start a year ago before turning it on over the back half of the year. Allen will be a high-end WR2 option Week 7 when the Chargers face the Titans in London.
report: Keenan Allen caught 4-of-6 targets for 62 yards while rushing four times for 41 yards in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Allen didn't get a ton of volume with Philip Rivers only attempting 26 passes. He had an on-field outburst after not getting targeted in the end-zone late in the fourth quarter. Allen has hit his floor all year but has only one touchdown. He's due for some positive regression in the second half.
report: Keenan Allen caught five passes for 72 yards in the Chargers' Week 7 win over the Titans.

impact: It was a nondescript night for Williams. He had a long run of 11 yards and fell out of the gameplan with the Packers airing it out in the second half. Williams is locked in as Green Bay's featured back for at least another week with Aaron Jones suspended, but he's going to face competition for carries when Jones returns.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed 15 times for 47 yards in Sunday night's Week 1 win over Chicago.

impact: Williams did not get much going against a tough defense, but he once again worked as the clear lead back ahead of Ty Montgomery. That could change moving forward, however, with Aaron Jones due back from suspension. Williams is a more reliable option in the passing game who had a two-week headstart on Jones, so he will likely retain the lead job. Even so, he will be a risky FLEX play next week in Washington.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed 16 times for 59 yards and hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 12 yards in the Packers' Week 2 tie with the Vikings.

impact: Williams got the start, but Aaron Jones drew as many touches in his 2018 debut. Jones out-gained Williams 47-45. Ty Montgomery out-produced both (64). Jones looked cannon shot whenever he was asked to change the pace. Williams' pass protection is going to keep him on the field, but the Packers — who need play-making targets — figure to start looking Jones and Ty Montgomery's way more and more. Williams' RB2 candidacy is on thin ice. The Pack host the Bills in Week 4.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed five times for 29 yards in the Packers' Week 3 loss to the Redskins, adding two receptions for 16 additional yards.

impact: Williams wasn't targeted in the passing game. Williams once again got the "start," but was once again out-gained by Aaron Jones, this time handily (82-27). Jones scored the Packers' lone ground touchdown. Williams is now averaging 3.44 yards per carry compared to 6.29 for Jones. The Pack like Williams' pass protection, but that production gulf can only go on for so long. Williams won't be a recommended FLEX against the Lions in Week 5.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed 11 times for 27 yards in the Packers' Week 4 win over the Bills.

impact: He added two catches for 19 yards on four targets.  Williams and Aaron Jones (seven carries, two catches) essentially split the run-down work, but the Packers fell behind big on the scoreboard and were down 24-0 at halftime.  It was mostly Ty Montgomery after the break.  Williams has been a big disappointment through five weeks.  Jones should get more chances to earn increased snaps moving forward.  Williams will be a low-upside RB3 next week against the 49ers.
report: Jamaal Williams rushed six times for 33 yards in the Packers' Week 5 loss to the Lions.

impact: A dream fantasy scenario unfolded once the Chargers fell behind 14-3 in the first quarter. Rivers is a legendary comeback-mode predator. He did not disappoint despite the best efforts of his receivers, who committed some truly horrifying drops. Tyrell Williams and Travis Benjamin both bungled certain touchdowns, while Rivers missed Benjamin on another. It was a thoroughly Chargers game, from the mistakes to the garbage time. Rivers gets the Bills on the road in Week 2. That's a long road trip.
report: Philip Rivers completed 34-of-51 passes for 424 yards, three touchdowns and an interception in the Chargers' 38-28, Week 1 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: It was a near-perfect game from Rivers, who didn't face any resistance from an injured Buffalo secondary. Rivers threw a touchdown to Mike Williams on the opening drive, with his other two coming on checkdowns to Melvin Gordon. This was another cupcake matchup for Rivers after shredding the Chiefs in the opener, but he's been locked in to start the year. The Chargers have a matchup with the Rams in Week 3.
report: Philip Rivers completed 23-of-27 passes for 256 yards and three touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 2 win over Buffalo.

impact: Coming off a three touchdown performance against the Bills, Rivers had a tougher matchup with the Rams this week, but he was still able to put together a respectable fantasy performance. Both touchdown passes went to Mike Williams who appears to have taken a second-year leap after being sidelined with injuries as a rookie. Rivers and the Chargers have an opportunity to get back in the win column next Sunday at home against the 49ers.
report: Philip Rivers completed 18-of-30 passes for 226 yards and two touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: Rivers passed John Elway for the eighth-most career passing yards in league history during the close home win. All three of his touchdown passes went to non-receivers, which will frustrate Keenan Allen and Mike Williams' fantasy owners, but Melvin Gordon and Austin Ekeler's receiving production is helping Rivers fill the stat sheet. Through four games, Rivers is averaging 289 passing yards and 2.75 touchdowns. He will be a QB1 next week against the Raiders.
report: Philip Rivers completed 25-of-39 passes for 250 yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: It was an extremely efficient afternoon for Rivers, who totaled just five incompletions en route to his second 300-plus yard performance on the year. Both scores came on throws out to the flats, including one in which he bobbled the snap, quickly regrouped, and side-armed a laser in the direction of Austin Ekeler (7-59-1), who shuffled his way past two defenders and into the end zone. Keenan Allen's touchdown toll has taken a hit this season, but Rivers has still stood upright as a strong QB1 due in part to the added involvement of both Melvin Gordon and Ekeler in Los Angeles' passing attack. Rivers is currently averaging 299 yards and 2.6 touchdowns through five games this season. He'll be a strong QB1 again in Week 6 against the Browns.
report: Philip Rivers completed 22-of-27 passes for 339 yards and two touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 5 victory over the Raiders.

impact: The 11 completions were the fewest in a game for Rivers since Week 16 of 2012. With the Chargers up big, he just wasn't needed as he attempted just five total passes in the second half on Sunday. Both of Rivers' scores went to Tyrell Williams in the second quarter. Rivers is having a tremendous start to the season with 15 touchdown passes to just three interceptions and will be in the lower-end QB1 mix next week in London versus the Titans.
report: Philip Rivers completed 11-of-20 passes for 207 yards with two touchdowns and one interception in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Rivers hit Tyrell Williams on a 75-yard bomb on the Chargers’ first play from scrimmage. Both of his touchdowns were 50-plus yards, with Mike Williams beating the Titans deep to open the second half. Rivers attempted only 26 passes but he's been a lot more efficient this year with a 17:3 TD/INT ratio. The Chargers are on bye next week, but Rivers will be in the lower-end QB1 mix against Seattle in Week 9.
report: Philip Rivers completed 19-of-26 passes for 306 yards and two touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 7 win over the Titans.

impact: Beathard did not officially record a stat, but he threw a beautiful pass to George Kittle in the end zone which was negated by a spurious offensive pass interference call. With Garoppolo likely looking at an ACL tear, Beathard is in line to take over the 49ers' starting job. He averaged 237 yards with three touchdowns and five interceptions in five starts last season.
report: C.J. Beathard replaced Jimmy Garoppolo (knee) in the 49ers' Week 3 loss to the Chiefs.

impact: Beathard wasn't so bad in the game with Kyle Shanahan only asking his quarterback to attempt two passes 20+ yards down the field. The 49ers might be able to dink-and-dunk their way down the field like they did today, but it's tough to imagine this offense being explosive with Beathard and a below average receiving group. He averaged 237 yards and only had three total touchdowns in five starts last season.
report: C.J. Beathard completed 23-of-37 passes for 298 yards, two touchdowns, and two interceptions in the 49ers' Week 4 loss to the Chargers.

impact: Beathard was also sacked four times for a loss of 49 yards. After playing surprisingly well in last week's loss to the Chargers, Beathard took a noticeable step back against the Cardinals. He was a turnover machine, throwing a pair of interceptions while also losing two fumbles. One of those fumbles was returned for a 23-yard touchdown in the fourth quarter, which essentially sealed the victory for Arizona. The 24-year-old benefited from garbage time, logging over 200 passing yards with San Francisco trailing in the second half. His lone rushing score came on a one-yard QB sneak. Outside of two-quarterback leagues, Beathard won't be someone fantasy owners can rely on next week at Green Bay.
report: C.J. Beathard completed 34-of-54 passes for 349 yards with two touchdowns and two interceptions while adding two carries for seven yards and another touchdown Sunday in the Niners’ Week 5 loss to the Cardinals.

impact: Beathard played so well for 58 minutes of this one.  He had a near-perfect passer rating and was carving up a banged-up Packers secondary, but a late interception with 1:07 left and the game tied at 30-30 set Aaron Rodgers up at his own 10-yard line.  The magic then happened, as Rodgers dropped dimes for 46 yards passing with a 21-yard scramble to finish the comeback.  Beathard's game can't go overlooked, though.  He threw 67- and 30-yard touchdowns to Marquise Goodwin, who roasted Kentrell Brice and Tramon Williams on each.  Beathard also showed big guts and toughness with 21 rushing yards, diving headfirst for first downs.  This was one of the most entertaining games of the year.  Beathard will do battle with the Rams in Santa Clara in Week 7.
report: C.J. Beathard completed 16-of-23 passes for 245 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception in the 49ers' 33-30, Week 6 loss to the Packers on Monday night.

impact: Beathard had a rough first half, turning the ball over twice including a lost fumble and failing to complete a pass to a receiver. He did find George Kittle for several big plays, however, including a 10-yard touchdown with just 10 seconds left to at least give the 49ers a chance. Unfortunately for San Francisco, he could not build on that drive in the second half, and he tossed another interception on a pass thrown slightly behind Kittle in the third quarter. Beathard has to take some blame for the showing, but he was constantly under pressure and ended up taking seven sacks. The road will not get any easier in Arizona against an underrated defense next week.
report: C.J. Beathard completed 15-of-27 passes for 170 yards, one touchdown, and two interceptions in the 49ers' Week 7 loss to the Rams.

impact: The Chargers were committed to exploiting the Chiefs' awful inside linebackers with Gordon and Austin Ekeler's receiving.
