Gordon's receptions matched a career high while the 100-yard day through the air was the first of his career. Whether it was via land or sky, Gordon was looking smooth and powerful, albeit against one of the league's worst defenses. Gordon did serious damage after first contact. Gordon will have a chance to get a hot streak going against the pathetic Bills in Week 2.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed 15 times for 64 yards in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs, adding a ridiculous nine receptions for 102 additional yards.

impact: Gordon did all of his damage in the first half. He went untouched on 20-yard run for his first score before beating the Bills for two red-zone TDs. Gordon was held in check on the ground, but his pass game usage continues to be encouraging. The Chargers rested Gordon most of the fourth quarter after picking up a minor injury. Gordon will remain a locked-in RB1 for Week 3 against the Rams.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed nine times for 28 yards and a touchdown and caught 6-of-7 passes for 38 yards and two touchdowns in the Chargers' Week 2 win over Buffalo.

impact: Gordon was fine on the ground -- 5.3 YPC and had an 11-yard touchdown -- but his receiving volume took an unexpected hit, even with the Chargers trailing for most of the game. Gordon had 15 receptions in his first two games, but only hauled in two passes against the Rams. Chargers coach Anthony Lynn has made it public that he wants to use Gordon as a receiver, so expect his receiving volume to rebound next Sunday against the 49ers. Gordon remains a locked-in RB1.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed 15 times for 80 yards and one touchdown and caught 2-of-4 targets for four yards in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: Gordon broke 100 rushing yards for the first time since Week 8 of 2017, but it's his workload as a receiver that makes Gordon so valuable. Gordon is essentially matching Keenan Allen's receiving production -- they both have 24 receptions on the year -- on top of his rushing stats. Gordon is averaging 118.75 total yards, 1.25 total touchdowns, and six receptions per game with the season 25 percent over. Gordon will be an elite RB1 next Sunday against the Raiders, who are currently getting shredded by Nick Chubb and Carlos Hyde.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed 15 times for 104 yards, and also added seven receptions for 55 yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: Gordon's across-the-board usage continued into Sunday as he hauled in all four of his targets for 62 yards. It wasn't pretty, but Gordon also mustered 58 yards rushing on a team-high 19 carries, out-touching teammate Austin Ekeler 23-7 on the day. With the Chargers leading big in the fourth quarter, Los Angeles rested Gordon on the team's final drive. Arguably the club's No. 2 receiver at this time, Gordon's weekly floor makes him as safe as any top option. He's now averaging 14.6 carries, 7.6 targets, and 119 total yards through five games this year. He'll remain an RB1 in Cleveland in Week 6.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed 19 times for 58 yards and one touchdown, adding four catches for 62 yards in the Chargers' week 5 victory over the Raiders.

impact: Gordon started the day with a 4-yard touchdown run on the Chargers' first possession of the game that got the ball rolling and the offense never looked back. He added touchdowns runs of 10 and 11 yards in the second half to bury the game. Gordon is off the best start of his career, rushing for 5.1 yards per carry through six games with nine total touchdowns. Gordon will be a set-and-forget option when the Chargers head to London in Week 7 versus the Titans.
report: Melvin Gordon rushed 18 times for 132 yards with three touchdowns while catching 2-of-4 targets for 18 yards in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: The 126 yards from scrimmage were a new career high. The Chargers were intent on featuring Ekeler and Melvin Gordon as pass catchers against the Chiefs' suspect linebacker corps. The mission was accomplished. Ekeler is still little more than an RB5/handcuff for fantasy purposes, though he would be an instant RB2 were Gordon to go down with injury.
report: Austin Ekeler caught 5-of-5 targets for 87 yards and a touchdown in the Chargers' Week 1 loss to the Chiefs, adding five carries for 39 additional yards.

impact: Ekeler was heavily involved for the second straight week. His touches were inflated with Melvin Gordon checking out with an injury in the fourth quarter, but it's becoming clear the Chargers have a role for Ekeler in their weekly gameplan. Ekeler is on the radar as a PPR FLEX for Week 3 against the Rams.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed 11 times for 77 yards and caught three passes for 21 yards in Week 2 against Buffalo.

impact: The Chargers have given Ekeler a small, defined role in the offense, and he is certainly making the most of his opportunities. Through three games, the change-of-pace back is averaging 8.15 yards per carry and 12 yards per reception. Ekeler is a weak PPR FLEX for Week 4 against the 49ers, but he would be an instant RB2 if Gordon ever misses time.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed four times for 44 yards and caught all three of his targets for 24 yards in the Chargers' Week 3 loss to the Rams.

impact: The Chargers have been giving Ekeler some looks every week behind Melvin Gordon, and he's been able to make the most of them. Today, Ekeler hauled in a 22-yard touchdown on a beautiful pass from Philip Rivers to save his fantasy day. It's nothing special, but Ekeler is a low-end FLEX option during the bye week season in 12-team leagues.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed eight times for 25 yards but caught 2-of-3 targets for 31 yards and touchdown in the Chargers' Week 4 win over the 49ers.

impact: Ekeler continued his 70-30 timeshare with teammate Melvin Gordon Sunday, being out-touched 23-7 on the day. Ekeler's carries primarily occurred in the team's final drive with the game already put to bed. His lone score was a terrific effort from both he and Philip Rivers, the latter who quickly recouped after bobbling the initial snap, looked to his right, and fired a laser to Ekeler, who broke ankles on his way into the end zone, in the flats. This performance puts Ekeler on pace for a standalone valuable 108-649 rushing and 44-662-9 receiving year.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed six times for 15 yards, additionally scampering for a 44-yard touchdown catch in the Chargers' Week 5 win over the Raiders.

impact: This was the first game in which Ekeler wasn't targeted in the passing game, but the Chargers threw just five passes in the second half. Ekeler is now averaging a gaudy 6.4 yards per carry now on the season in relief of Melvin Gordon. He will enter Week 7 as a FLEX option when the Chargers face the Titans in London.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed seven times for 60 yards in Sunday's Week 6 win over the Browns.

impact: Ekeler got the start with Melvin Gordon out. This was one of his worse games of the year despite the expanded role. The Chargers scored both of their touchdowns on deep shots, so there wasn't a ton of red-zone opportunities for Ekeler. With Los Angeles on a bye, Ekeler looks destined to resume a change-up role in Week 9.
report: Austin Ekeler rushed 12 times for 42 yards and caught 5-of-7 passes for 26 yards in the  Chargers' Week 7 win over the Titans.

impact: Swoope played behind Mo Alie-Cox in the Colts' backup tight end timeshare with Eric Ebron out in front.  Swoope is a Dynasty stash but nothing more.
report: Erik Swoope caught 1-of-2 targets for a two-yard touchdown in the Colts' Week 6 loss to the Jets.

impact: Swoope was questionable for this game with a knee injury and may have aggravated it. He caught his lone target for a 17-yard touchdown off a play-action pass from Andrew Luck before exiting in the second quarter. With Swoope banged up and Jack Doyle (hip) inactive, the Colts are looking thin at tight end behind Eric Ebron.
report: Colts TE Erik Swoope (knee) left Sunday's Week 7 game against the Bills and is questionable to return.

impact: Rogers entered Sunday with eight catches for 49 yards on 10 targets.  He was far more active in this one after T.Y. Hilton had to leave multiple times with chest and hamstring injuries.  Rogers' 11 targets matched Nyheim Hines for the team lead on a day Andrew Luck attempted 62 passes.  With Hilton expected to miss Thursday night's Week 5 game against the Patriots, Rogers will again be relied upon.  He may have some WR5 appeal in deeper leagues in a likely catchup-mode game.
report: Chester Rogers caught 8-of-11 targets for 85 yards in the Colts' Week 4 loss to the Texans.

impact: Rogers got off to an excruciating start with multiple dropped passes.  He salvaged his fantasy bottom line on a 17-yard garbage-time touchdown with Indianapolis down multiple scores.  Nevertheless, Rogers is suddenly in prime fantasy position as the Colts lost several more pass catchers to injury on Sunday, including Ryan Grant (ankle).  With double-digit targets in three straight games, Rogers will be a fantasy starter in Week 7 versus Buffalo.
report: Chester Rogers caught 4-of-10 targets for 55 yards and a touchdown in the Colts' Week 6 loss to the Jets.

impact: The bulk of his yards came on one catch, a 29-yard grab on a play where the defense forgot about him during the second quarter. That was the Colts' longest play from scrimmage. Rogers couldn't take advantage of Ryan Grant's absence, though that was mostly because the Colts stopped throwing after getting ahead early. The 25-year-old could be in play as a DFS dart throw if Grant remains sidelined for Week 8 against the Raiders.
report: Chester Rogers came down with four catches for 40 yards on four targets Sunday in Indianapolis’ Week 7 win over the Bills.

impact: It's the last thing the Bengals need after losing Tyler Eifert. Kroft's absence locks C.J. Uzomah into an every-down role.
report: Bengals TE Tyler Kroft left Week 5 against Miami with a foot injury and is questionable to return.

impact: Golladay did most of his work well before this one got out of hand in the third quarter.  At one point, he was leading the Lions with eight targets before Golden Tate ended the night with 15 and a touchdown.  Golladay also made one of the best plays of the night for the Lions, decking CB Trumaine Johnson after an interception, forcing a fumble and recovering it on his own in Jets territory.  Unfortunately, the Lions did nothing with it.  Golladay played a career-high 65 snaps (hat tip to PFF's Nathan Jahnke) and needs to be added where he's available.  Golladay will head into Week 2 at San Francisco as a big-play threat WR3/4.
report: Kenny Golladay caught 7-of-12 targets for 114 yards in the Lions' 48-17, Week 1 loss to the Jets on Monday night.

impact: He caught Ahkello Witherspoon napping on his 30-yard touchdown in the first quarter, which accounted for the Lions’ first points of the afternoon. Golladay didn’t score again but he was a consistent presence in the Lions’ passing game, just as he was a week ago when he registered a career-high 114 yards in a loss to the Jets. The 24-year-old showed flashes as a rookie but struggled to stay healthy. Now he’s in the midst of a sophomore breakout and has risen to must-start status in all formats. Look for Golladay to keep the train rolling next week against New England.
report: Kenny Golladay finished with six catches for 89 yards and a touchdown on nine targets Sunday in the Lions’ Week 2 loss to San Francisco.

impact: Golladay continued to start over Golden Tate in two-wide sets. He scored the Lions' first touchdown of the game, extending the ball across the goal-line on a play where he was tackled at the one-yard line. Golladay has at least 100 yards or a touchdown in every game this season. He's a WR2 for Week 4's matchup with the Cowboys.
report: Kenny Golladay caught 6-of-7 passes for 53 yards and a touchdown in the Lions' Week 3 win over the Patriots.

impact: Even with Golladay seeing his lowest target total of the season, the second-year wideout was still reasonably productive in the loss to Dallas. While Golladay’s shrinking volume is somewhat concerning, the 24-year-old has established a nice floor for himself, topping 50 yards in all four games this year after reaching that mark just five times all of last season. He’ll be safe to employ as a WR3/flex against the Packers in Week 5.
report: Kenny Golladay came down with four catches for 74 yards on four targets Sunday in Detroit’s Week 4 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: Golladay caught a 47-yard touchdown in the first quarter, but it was called back on an illegal hands to the face penalty.  He then went 60 yards down the sideline on his first official catch, stiff-arming a defender to the ground before being tackled inside the 10-yard line only to see LeGarrette Blount score a couple plays later.  Golladay eventually found the end zone from five yards away in the second half, and his nine targets led the team on a day Matthew Stafford attempted just 26 passes with the Lions holding a commanding lead much of the afternoon.  Golladay has seen at least nine targets in 3-of-5 games and is a locked-in WR2 heading into the bye.
report: Kenny Golladay caught 4-of-9 targets for 98 yards and one touchdown in the Lions' 31-23, Week 5 win over the Packers.

impact: Golladay also drew a 15-yard DPI. Golladay drew zero first half targets in what ended up a nightmare fantasy day. Golladay nearly saved it with a 13-yard score in the second half, but it was called back by a Lions penalty. The Dolphins' secondary did an excellent job on each of the Lions' "big three." Golladay now has just 10 catches over his past three games. He will look to heat back up in Week 8 against the Seahawks.
report: Kenny Golladay caught 2-of-2 targets for 37 yards in the Lions' Week 7 win over the Dolphins.

impact: Latimer was injured covering a fourth quarter punt. The Giants' No. 3 receiver had caught 3-of-4 targets for 52 yards before going down. With Nos. 1 and 2 tight ends Evan Engram and Rhett Ellison sidelined, Latimer set a new season-high for yardage in his three quarters of play.
report: Giants WR Cody Latimer was forced from Thursday's game against the Eagles with a hamstring injury and will not return.

impact: Lockett did not do much in this game, but he was able to get open deep where Russell Wilson hit him for a 51-yard touchdown. That kind of play makes Lockett an interesting dart throw every week, but he needs to produce more consistently to be a reliable fantasy option. With Doug Baldwin dealing with a knee injury, he might get his chance moving forward. Lockett should be added in most leagues.
report: Tyler Lockett hauled in 3-of-4 targets for 59 yards and a touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 1 loss to the Broncos.

impact: Lockett now has 3-59-1 and 5-60-1 lines to open the season.  Both touchdowns took big plays to score, as Lockett made a near-impossible grab draped in CB Kyle Fuller's coverage in the back corner of the end zone from 19 yards out in this one.  Fuller should have been flagged for interference but it didn't matter.  Lockett is very boom-or-bust-ish but gets a tasty date with the Cowboys at home in Week 3.  He'll be on the WR4 radar for that one.
report: Tyler Lockett caught 5-of-7 targets for 60 yards and one touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 2 loss to the Bears.

impact: He did most of his damage on one play, breaking off a 52-yard touchdown late in the first half on a play where Kavon Frazier blew his assignment. That was about it for Lockett, though the long touchdown may have been enough to push fantasy owners over the top. Lockett should remain Russell Wilson’s top receiving weapon in Doug Baldwin’s absence, though a tough matchup against Cardinals All-Pro corner Patrick Peterson awaits him in Week 4.
report: Tyler Lockett collected four catches for 77 yards and a touchdown on six targets Sunday in the Seahawks’ Week 3 win over the Cowboys.

impact: Lockett was second on the team in targets with Doug Baldwin returning to action, but led the team in receiving yardage on Sunday. After scoring in the opening three weeks of the season, Lockett failed to reach the end zone for the first time this season. With Baldwin returning, Lockett will be a WR3/FLEX option Week 5 when the Seahawks host the Rams.
report: Tyler Lockett caught 5-of-6 targets for 53 yards in Sunday's Week 4 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Lockett made the most of his opportunities in a game Russell Wilson completed just 13 passes. His touchdown was a 39-yarder on which he ran right past Marcus Peters, and he ran a great route to get the safety turned around on a 44-yard gain in the fourth quarter. With the Seahawks running a run-heavy, deep-shot offense, Lockett might end up being their most valuable fantasy receiver. He will have a good shot at some more big plays next week against the Raiders in London.
report: Tyler Lockett hauled in 3-of-5 targets for 98 yards and a touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 5 loss to the Rams.

impact: Lockett has now scored in 5-of-6 games.  Unfortunately, he was otherwise quiet in a game where the Seahawks leaned heavily on their rushing attack, and Doug Baldwin was Seattle's lone player to exceed four targets.  The Seahawks have a Week 7 bye forthcoming.  Lockett has earned every-week WR3/flex treatment.
report: Tyler Lockett caught 3-of-4 targets for 13 yards and a touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 6 blowout win over the Raiders.

impact: He out-targeted John Ross 5 to 2.  Boyd is unlikely to be a fantasy factor behind A.J. Green, Joe Mixon, and Tyler Eifert, but he has a more secure role than the Bengals' hyped sophomore wideout as Cincy's locked-in slot man.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 3-of-5 targets for 26 yards in the Bengals' Week 1 win over the Colts.

impact: Boyd was a monster in Week 2 against the Ravens, and he stepped up to become Andy Dalton's favorite target on Sunday as A.J. Green (groin) exited early in the third quarter and never returned.  Dalton hit Boyd for a spectacular 27-yard rollout touchdown, then found Boyd open off a broken play in the second half for a 49-yard gain.  Dalton is looking for Boyd when he's in trouble.  Boyd has earned WR3 treatment entering Week 4 at Atlanta, and could push for WR2 value if Green can't play.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 6-of-7 targets for 132 yards and a touchdown in the Bengals' Week 3 loss to Carolina.

impact: An established factor in Cincinnati's offense at this point, Boyd was one of Andy Dalton's favorite targets all game, but he was spectacular on the game-winning touchdown drive, converting a third down and two fourth downs. He now has two 100-yard games in a row after zero in the first 28 games of his career. With Dalton playing great and Tyler Eifert likely out for the year, Boyd should return at worst WR3 value the rest of the way.
report: Tyler Boyd hauled in 11-of-15 targets for 100 yards in the Bengals' Week 4 win over the Falcons.

impact: It's a step back after Boyd went over 90 yards the last three weeks. The Bengals went run heavy against Miami, leaving just seven targets for Boyd behind A.J. Green. With Tyler Eifert on IR, there's a lot to like with Boyd's ROS outlook. He'll be a WR3 for a plus Week 6 matchup with the Steelers.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 4-of-7 passes for 44 yards in Week 5 against the Dolphins.

impact: His nine looks were second on the team to A.J. Green's dozen.  Boyd was the recipient of both of Andy Dalton's touchdowns, from two and 14 yards out, and Boyd had to make a diving catch on the two-yarder.  He made a number of difficult grabs in this one on a day Dalton was off the mark.  Boyd has been a steady WR2 for weeks and will stay that way next week against the Chiefs.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 7-of-9 targets for 62 yards and two touchdowns in the Bengals' 28-21, Week 6 loss to the Steelers.

impact: Boyd was invisible in the first half, getting held without a catch. He managed to get some targets late with the Bengals airing it out, but it's a disappointing game. Boyd has been held under 50 yards in two of the last three weeks. He'll be a low-end WR2 for Week 8 against the Bucs.
report: Tyler Boyd caught 2-of-4 passes for 27 yards in Week 7 against the Chiefs.

impact: The Chiefs romped, but Kelce continued his recent trend of quiet games against the Bolts. He has just two catches in two career games in "StubHub Center." The Chiefs have so many weapons that down weeks are bound to happen for Kelce, but he will be back out there as a top-three TE1 against the Steelers in Week 2. Patrick Mahomes has the looks of a quarterback who is going to get all of his studs big plays.
report: Travis Kelce caught just 1-of-6 targets for six yards in the Chiefs' Week 1 win over the Chargers.

impact: One week after he was held to one catch against the Chargers, Kelce erupted for just the third two-touchdown game of his career. Kelce split CB Cameron Sutton and LB Jon Bostic on his first score, corralling an absolute laser from Patrick Mahomes. For the second, he caught a low throw near the goal line for a 25-yarder. Kelce will get the 49ers in what could be a high-scoring Week 3 affair.
report: Travis Kelce caught 7-of-10 targets for 109 yards and two touchdowns in the Chiefs' Week 2 win over the Steelers.

impact: Patrick Mahomes spread the ball around in this one, but he kept coming back to Kelce, who was seemingly open on every play. The tight end finished the first half with 93 yards including a great one-handed grab in the two-minute drill, and he could have had a bigger day if the Chiefs were forced to throw more in the second half. He will remain a top-two tight end option next week in Denver.
report: Travis Kelce hauled in 8-of-10 targets for 114 yards in the Chiefs' Week 3 win over the 49ers.

impact: Kelce went catch-less on three targets in the first half but became Patrick Mahomes' go-to option after the break.  His touchdown came on a short pop pass to the right from two yards out in the fourth quarter.  Later in the same quarter, Kelce was drilled in the stomach and ribs area on an end-zone target and buckled to the ground before leaving the field with trainers.  It's possible he simply had the wind knocked out of him.  After catching one pass for six yards in the opener, Kelce has 22 catches for 301 yards and three touchdowns the last three weeks.  He gets the Jaguars in Week 5.
report: Travis Kelce caught 7-of-12 targets for 78 yards and one touchdown in the Chiefs' Week 4 win over the Broncos on Monday night.

impact: Kelce continued to look like the best tight end in the league in this one. He shook Telvin Smith to get open for a 15-yard catch on the opening drive, and he left Barry Church in the dust when he put on the brakes and changed direction on his 40-yard catch-and-run in the second quarter. He should have had a touchdown on that drive, but he dropped the pass. Kelce now has at least 100 yards in three of his last four games. He will be the top option at tight end next week in New England.
report: Travis Kelce hauled in 5-of-8 targets for 100 yards in the Chiefs' Week 5 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Kelce got most of his yards on a 44-yard third down catch in the first quarter. He led the Chiefs in receiving, but was faded in the red-zone in favor of Kareem Hunt and Demetrius Harris. Kelce has been held out of the end-zone in three straight weeks. He's due for some positive regression in Week 8 against Denver.
report: Travis Kelce caught five passes for 95 yards in Week 7 against the Bengals.

impact: Wright went 3-23 on five targets in Week 1 and seems to have carved out the slot job for the Panthers.  Cam Newton really had an affinity for him on third down, especially with no Greg Olsen (foot) in the lineup.  Wright's touchdown came on third down from five yards out.  There are worse players to roster in deep PPR leagues.  The Panthers get the Bengals in Week 3.
report: Jarius Wright caught 5-of-7 targets for 62 yards and one touchdown in the Panthers' Week 2 loss to the Falcons.

impact: Smith is a "starter," but he has no fantasy value.  During their Week 4 bye, the Panthers need to find a way to cut Smith's snaps in favor of D.J. Moore.
report: Torrey Smith caught 3-of-6 targets for 19 yards in the Panthers' Week 3 win over the Bengals.

impact: Smith was completely anonymous despite seeing the field on 45-of-71 offensive snaps, but at least he got in some good cardio. Cam Newton must have either forgotten he existed or just chose not to acknowledge him. Either way, the well-traveled 29-year-old can be safely ignored in all fantasy formats.
report: Torrey Smith came up empty on his lone target Sunday in the Panthers’ Week 5 victory over New York.

impact: Smith, whose touchdown came on a goal line look, also converted a two-point attempt. The score was Smith's second as a Panther. Smith just crossed the 100-yard threshold for the season this afternoon. He's miles from fantasy relevance.
report: Torrey Smith caught 5-of-5 targets for 43 yards and a touchdown in the Panthers' Week 6 loss to the Redskins.

impact: He was seen limping to the X-ray room after the game.  Smith contributed a massive 35-yard catch on fourth down with only a few minutes remaining to keep alive what wound up being the game-winning drive. Smith finished with four catches for 61 yards on six targets. If he can’t play in Week 8 against the Ravens, D.J. Moore and Curtis Samuel could get more playing time.
report: Torrey Smith needed X-rays following Sunday’s Week 7 win over Philadelphia.

impact: Jones was targeted on a couple deep balls, but he and Matthew Stafford were unable to hook up on any big plays against an underrated Jets secondary.  Better days are obviously ahead.  Jones will be a WR2 next week in San Francisco.
report: Marvin Jones caught 4-of-8 targets for 54 yards in the Lions' Week 1 loss to the Jets.

impact: Jones routinely created separation from the Niners' secondary but Matthew Stafford couldn’t find his deep ball on Sunday. The most egregious misfire from Stafford came in the second quarter when Jones had nothing but green grass in front of him but the two couldn’t connect. That must have been frustrating for fantasy owners, though Stafford delivered a peace offering in the form of a five-yard touchdown pass to Jones with 8:36 left in the fourth quarter. Jones has now caught exactly four passes for 54 yards in each of his first two games. Say what you will about Marvin, but at least the man's consistent. Jones and the Lions will host the Patriots in Week 3.
report: Marvin Jones hauled in four catches for 54 yards and a touchdown Sunday in the Lions’ Week 2 loss to the 49ers.

impact: Jones was a late addition to the injury report, getting in a limited practice Friday. He'll be monitored throughout the day, but it sounds like the Lions are expecting him to play. Jones was getting outsnapped by Kenny Golladay before going down and could see his role scaled back at less than 100 percent. He can't be trusted in Week 3 lineups.
report: NFL Network's Ian Rapoport reports "there's optimism" Marvin Jones (questionable, ankle) plays in Sunday night's game with the Patriots.

impact: Darius Slay (concussion) is also active after being listed as questionable. Jones went down late in the practice week and came down to a game-time decision, so his snaps may be limited. The Lions will be without Ziggy Ansah (shoulder) for Sunday night's game. Ameer Abdullah, DE Kerry Hyder, OG Joe Dahl, OT Andrew Donnal and WR Brandon Powell are also inactive.
report: Marvin Jones (ankle) is active for Week 3 against the Patriots.

impact: Jones started and looked close to 100 percent playing through his ankle injury. He got wide open out of the slot for a deep 33-yard touchdown for his only highlight of the night. Jones finished behind Golden Tate (8) and Kenny Golladay (7) in targets, but there hasn't been much dropoff from his strong 2017. Jones is a FLEX play for Week 4 against the Cowboys.
report: Marvin Jones caught 4-of-6 passes for 69 yards and a touchdown in Week 3 against the Patriots.

impact: Jones made a highlight-reel catch in the second quarter, pulling in an absurd over-the-shoulder grab to beat Chidobe Awuzie for a 34-yard pickup. He was targeted in the end zone later in the half but the pass from Matthew Stafford was off the mark. Jones hasn’t had a blow-up game yet in 2018 and it’s fair to expect fewer of those this season with Kenny Golladay becoming a bigger part of the Lions’ passing game. Of course, both of them took a backseat to Golden Tate (8-132-2) on Sunday. Jones will be a mere WR3 next week against the Packers.
report: Marvin Jones chipped in with three catches for 56 yards on six targets Sunday in the Lions’ Week 4 loss to the Cowboys.

impact: Jones was a late addition to the injury report during the week but is good enough to go in the NFC North tilt.  At less than 100 percent and with Kenny Golladay and Golden Tate balling, Jones is a boom-bust WR3 play.
report: Marvin Jones (ankle) is active for Week 5 against the Packers.

impact: Playing through an ankle injury, Jones made his one catch count with a diving touchdown in the back of the end zone.  He almost had a second score from 42 yards out on a shot play when the defense jumped offside, but Jones was unable to control the ball through the ground after diving for it.  Jones gets a week to rest and get healthy with the Lions heading into their bye.
report: Marvin Jones caught an eight-yard touchdown on four targets in the Lions' Week 5 win over the Packers.

impact: Jones also drew a 25-yard DPI. It was a quiet day for the Lions' entire receiver corps, but Jones now has just 93 yards over his past three games. He is averaging a disappointing 45 on the year. Jones should still have blow-up games, but Kenny Golladay's emergence has rendered him a low-end WR3 in fantasy.
report: Marvin Jones caught 3-of-4 targets for 29 yards in the Lions' Week 7 win over the Dolphins.

impact: Gallman was working as the clear No. 2 running back behind Saquon Barkley, but he picked up a knee injury in the third quarter. Jonathan Stewart, who has not lost a step, will serve as the backup while Gallman is out.
report: Giants RB Wayne Gallman (knee) is questionable to return Week 1 against the Jaguars.

impact: Gallman left Week 1 against the Jaguars with a knee injury, but he said that was just precautionary. The sophomore was working as the No. 2 back before going down.
report: Wayne Gallman (knee) expects to play Week 2.

impact: Conley's score was a bullet on a first quarter post route. Conley got the inside track on Artie Burns. It was a nice play, but Conley has just three targets through two games. Patrick Mahomes is working miracles, but he can't make Conley fantasy relevant.
report: Chris Conley caught 2-of-2 targets for 17 yards and a touchdown in the Chiefs' Week 2 win over the Steelers.

impact: Hill also rushed twice for four yards. It was a completely ridiculous performance, with Hill's punt return score the Chiefs' first touch of the season. He added a 58-yard receiving touchdown just seven minutes later. Hill's second passing strike was a one-yard shovel from Patrick Mahomes. There was a scary moment in the first quarter when Hill was evaluated for both a concussion and shoulder injury after an awkward landing, but he was cleared to remain in the game. The dream chemistry Hill displayed with Mahomes in the preseason carried over against the Chargers' (supposedly) elite defense. Hill gets the Steelers in Week 2.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 7-of-8 targets for 169 yards and a pair of touchdowns in the Chiefs' Week 1 win over the Chargers, adding a 91-yard punt return score.

impact: Hill wasn't even targeted in the first half, so 5/90/1 was quite an accomplishment, even if that's quiet by Hill's standards. Hill's score was a 29-yarder where he got several steps on Artie Burns down the left sideline. Hill will try to torment the 49ers in the Chiefs' Week 3 home opener.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 5-of-6 targets for 90 yards and a touchdown in the Chiefs' Week 2 win over the Steelers.

impact: With Patrick Mahomes spreading the ball around, Hill did not have a blow-up game, but he still made his presence known by going up high to reel in a 42-yard catch in the second quarter. He also should have had a 49-yard touchdown, but Mahomes just underthrew him, allowing the defender to catch up. Hill will have some down games, but his upside is as high as any receiver in the league. He will remain a locked-in WR1 next week against the Broncos.
report: Tyreek Hill hauled in 2-of-5 targets for 51 yards in the Chiefs' Week 3 win over the 49ers.

impact: He "added" two yards on one carry.  The Broncos did a really good job of containing Hill, but Travis Kelce and Kareem Hunt were able to pick up the slack, combining for 253 yards and a couple scores.  Hill has had a quiet last two games with no touchdowns and will be a WR2 next week vs. Jacksonville.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 9-of-13 targets for 54 yards in the Chiefs' Week 4 win over the Broncos.

impact: Jalen Ramsey's shadow should be Hill's toughest test of the season, but that did not stop him from making big plays. He opened the game with a 40-yard run on Kansas City's first offensive play, although it was reduced to 21 yards because of a penalty. He added a 36-yard catch in the third quarter on a great throw by Patrick Mahomes. Always a threat for a big play, Hill should have a much easier time next week in New England.
report: Tyreek Hill hauled in 4-of-7 targets for 61 yards and rushed twice for 26 yards in the Chiefs' Week 5 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Even the huge stats don't do justice to how good of a night Hill had. Hill’s first two touchdowns came in the red-zone, and he smoked the Patriots on a blown assignment for a 75-yard TD to tie the game with under four minutes. Hill got most of his yardage on chunk plays, but his speed was too much for New England's zone schemes. It’s a needed breakout for Hill after he'd been held to 166 scoreless yards over the last three games. Hill is in a great spot against the Bengals in another Sunday night matchup next week.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 7-of-12 targets for 142 yards and three touchdowns in the Chiefs' Week 6 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Hill was featured heavily but didn’t break any huge plays. He should've had a 35-yard touchdown but dropped a wide open pass in the end-zone. Hill made up for it a few plays later with a goal-line TD. He's now scored touchdowns in consecutive games after a three-week scoring drought. Hill has a matchup with the Broncos in Week 8.
report: Tyreek Hill caught 7-of-10 passes for 68 yards and a touchdown in Week 7 against the Bengals.

impact: Drawing the start for the injured Chris Carson, Davis dominated the Seattle backfield on Sunday, handling 25-of-34 backfield touches. Davis gave Seattle the lead with a 20-yard touchdown in the 1st quarter and then scored their second and final touchdown on a 1-yard plunge in the 3rd quarter. Davis' fantasy viability will be contingent on the availability of Carson in Week against the Rams.
report: Mike Davis rushed 21 times for 101 yards and two touchdowns while catching four passes for 23 yards in Sunday's Week 4 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Davis ceded the starting job and many of the early carries to Chris Carson, but his role in the offense grew as the game went along. Most importantly, he received the most valuable carry of the afternoon. After Carson drove the offense down the field with some big runs, Davis took over, converted a third-and-two, and then scored from six yards out on the next play. Davis looks like he is the No. 2 option in the backfield -- Carson ended with 20 touches to 14 for Davis -- but the Seahawks' running game has been good enough to support multiple fantasy players the last several weeks. His workload could prove shaky, but Davis will be worth a look in FLEX spots next week against the Raiders in London.
report: Mike Davis rushed 12 times for 68 yards and a touchdown in the Seahawks' Week 5 loss to the Rams.

impact: It was surprising to see Davis handle only seven touches while Rashaad Penny came back to life for 11, although the blowout nature of the game skewed usage a bit, and it was an opportunity for the Seahawks' coaching staff to give Penny more chances.  Davis is worth rostering as an RB4/5, but he won't become a consistent flex option barring injury to Carson and/or Penny.
report: Mike Davis rushed six times for 21 yards and caught 1-of-3 targets for five yards in Seattle's Week 6 London win over Oakland.

impact: It was a frustrating yet familiar day for Wilson. His offensive line struggled to protect him, and his receivers struggled to get open. Even so, he managed to create several big plays and keep Seattle in the game until the end. Wilson could face a similar script next week against the Bears and Khalil Mack, but he will remain a solid QB1.
report: Russell Wilson completed 19-of-33 passes for 298 yards, three touchdowns, and two interceptions in the Seahawks' Week 1 loss to the Broncos.

impact: He rushed for just 17 yards and fumbled twice, losing one.  Wilson entered the fourth quarter with 69 passing yards and went into halftime with 68 through the air.  He took six sacks for the second-straight week to open the season and continues to hold onto the ball far too long in an attempt to create offense for a talentless unit that also can't block.  Wilson had far fewer than 200 pass yards before the meaningless final drive with under a minute left where the Bears played no defense, allowing a short Will Dissly touchdown at the end.  Wilson is an incredible quarterback but is being suffocated in Seattle under OC Brian Schottenheimer, playing behind a peewee league offensive line, along with a running game that still does nothing.  Wilson gets the Cowboys at home in Week 3.  Good luck to fantasy owners.  Wilson finished just ahead of Blaine Gabbert and Josh Allen in the Week 2 fantasy standings at quarterback.
report: Russell Wilson completed 22-of-36 passes for 226 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception in the Seahawks' 24-17, Week 2 loss to the Bears on Monday night.

impact: He was sacked twice for a loss of 10 yards. Playing without top receiver Doug Baldwin for the second straight week, Wilson was a game manager on Sunday, spending most of his afternoon handing off to running back Chris Carson. It was a workmanlike effort for Wilson, though he did supply one big play, uncorking a 52-yard touchdown to Tyler Lockett late in the second quarter. Wilson gets the winless Cardinals on the road in Week 4.
report: Russell Wilson completed 16-of-26 passes for 192 yards and a pair of touchdowns while losing a yard on two carries Sunday in the Seahawks’ Week 3 win over the Cowboys.

impact: Wilson added 21 yards on four rushes on the ground. Wilson played a clean game, but once again failed to add much fantasy production. He has now finished in the bottom-half of quarterback scoring in three consecutive games since opening the season as QB1 on the road. Wilson will enter Week 2 as a high-QB2 option Week 5 at home against the Rams.
report: Russell Wilson completed 19-of-26 passes for 172 yards with no touchdowns or interceptions in Sundays Week 4 win over the Cardinals.

impact: The Seahawks continue to lean on the running game, limiting Wilson to just 73 attempts in the last three games, but the quarterback was able to help his fantasy backers out with big plays and touchdowns. Wilson found Tyler Lockett for two long plays including a touchdown, and he hit David Moore for 30-yard and three-yard scores. The three-yarder was vintage as Wilson created time in the backfield and found Moore in the back of the end zone just before going out of bounds. Wilson has a great matchup next week against the Raiders in London, but he will be nothing more than a low-end QB1 because of his attempt concerns.
report: Russell Wilson completed 13-of-21 passes for 198 yards and three touchdowns in the Seahawks' Week 5 loss to the Rams.

impact: Wilson rushed six times for 20 yards, but he looked relatively sluggish on his carries while dealing with a hamstring injury.  The good news is Wilson got it done through the air, and Seattle has a forthcoming Week 7 bye for Wilson to rest his ailing leg.  Even while missing his early-season dual threat due to the hamstring, Wilson has flirted with QB1 production.  It would not be surprising if Wilson delivered one of his trademark second-half explosions.
report: Russell Wilson completed 17-of-23 passes for 222 yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the Seahawks' Week 6 drubbing of the Raiders.

impact: Dalton was mostly sharp, keeping his eyes downfield when pressured and hitting A.J. Green and John Ross for scores.  Green's TD came from 38 yards out on a bomb, and Ross' from three yards away on an end-zone fade.  This is the best supporting cast Dalton has been surrounded by since the 2015 season, when he finished as a top-seven quarterback in fantasy points per game.  Dalton will be a mid-range QB2 in a tough Week 2 matchup with Baltimore, however.
report: Andy Dalton completed 21-of-28 passes for 243 yards, two touchdowns, and an interception in the Bengals' Week 1 win over the Colts.

impact: It was one of the shakiest four-touchdown performances you will ever see. Dalton was excellent in the first half, piling up all four of his scores. After the break, he could barely get a first down and was lucky to escape without a turnover. Dalton relentlessly worked his connection with A.J. Green, finding him for three of his four TDs. Dalton also displayed strong chemistry with Tyler Boyd, a welcome development as the Bengals try to deepen their weapons arsenal. The Bengals head on the road to Carolina for Week 3.
report: Andy Dalton completed 24-of-42 passes for 265 yards and four touchdowns in the Bengals' 34-23, Week 2 win over the Ravens.

impact: The four picks make Dalton's game look worse than it was; one was tipped high into the air on a target Josh Malone couldn't haul in, and Dalton's fourth INT came on what amounted to a last-gasp Hail Mary heave.  Of more concern are the Bengals' mounting injuries; after Joe Mixon had his knee scoped in Week 2, A.J. Green left Sunday's loss with a groin pull and did not return.  Dalton's Week 4 fantasy upside at Atlanta will hinge largely on Green's availability.
report: Andy Dalton completed 29-of-46 passes for 352 yards, two touchdowns, and four interceptions in the Bengals' Week 3 loss to Carolina.

impact: Dalton was exceptional throughout this game -- he completed 14-of-16 passes for 211 yards and two touchdowns in the first half -- but he made his money with the win in the balance late in the fourth quarter. Down five, Dalton led a 16-play, 75-yard touchdown drive in which he found Tyler Boyd for two fourth-down conversions. The touchdown was a great throw to A.J. Green in the end zone. Dalton now has multiple touchdowns in every game and has topped 335 yards each of the last two weeks. He will be a back-end QB1 next week against the Dolphins.
report: Andy Dalton completed 29-of-41 passes for 337 yards, three touchdowns, and an interception in the Bengals' Week 4 win over the Falcons.

impact: Dalton's only touchdown was a broken play where he hit Joe Mixon in the end-zone on a back-shoulder throw. He was picked trying to force a pass in the red-zone, but otherwise managed the game effectively. It's a disappointing game from Dalton against a Miami pass rush that was missing multiple starters. Dalton has another plus matchup with the Steelers in Week 6.
report: Andy Dalton completed 20-of-30 passes for 248 yards with a touchdown and an interception in the Bengals' Week 5 win over the Dolphins.

impact: Dalton averaged a pitiful 5.5 yards per attempt and took three sacks.  He needed to play much better for the Bengals but was also hurt bad by a couple drops.  Dalton just didn't seem to be on his A-game in this one, misfiring on a couple throws.  Tyler Boyd had to make a pair of shoe-string, diving catches, with one coming on a two-yard touchdown.  Dalton's now had back-to-back mediocre outings ahead of a ripe Week 7 spot against the Chiefs.
report: Andy Dalton completed 26-of-42 passes for 229 yards and two touchdowns in the Bengals' Week 6 loss to the Steelers.

impact: The Bengals got off to a sluggish start, but Dalton managed a first-quarter touchdown to C.J. Uzomah. He telegraphed a pick-six on the first drive of second half and couldn’t get anything going after that. It’s one of the worst starts of the season for Dalton, who’s had multiple TDs in 5-of-7 games. Dalton has a rebound matchup with the Bucs in Week 8
report: Andy Dalton completed 15-of-29 passes for 148 yards with a touchdown and an interception in Week 7 against Kansas City.

impact: Riddick led all Lions running backs playing 40 snaps with Detroit getting annihilated on the scoreboard and playing catchup most of the night.  Riddick still did nothing with his looks despite seeing a goal-line carry, where he was predictably stonewalled.  Riddick isn't fantasy starter material outside of deep PPR leagues where he'll have some bye-week value.
report: Theo Riddick rushed four times for 20 yards and caught 5-of-7 targets for 15 yards in the Lions' Week 1 loss to the Jets.

impact: He didn’t see any chances as a ball-carrier but was targeted heavily in the passing game with the Lions playing from behind in the second half. Riddick may not sleep well tonight after dropping a third-down pass from Matthew Stafford with the Lions driving late in the fourth quarter. Stafford went right back to Riddick, who was wide-open on the following play, but his pass fell incomplete. That ended Detroit’s comeback bid with 14 seconds remaining. Though he technically plays running back, Riddick is really more of a wide receiver. He gets the Patriots at home next week.
report: Theo Riddick secured nine-of-12 targets for 47 yards Sunday in Detroit’s Week 2 loss to the 49ers.

impact: As usual, Riddick worked mostly as a pass-catcher, seeing just one carry in the loss. All five of his touches came before halftime. With Kerryon Johnson and LeGarrette Blount getting most of the backfield work for Detroit, Riddick is just a bench stash in PPR leagues. He’ll get the Packers at home in Week 5.
report: Theo Riddick gained seven yards on his lone carry while nabbing four catches for 20 yards on five targets Sunday in the Lions’ Week 4 loss to Dallas.

impact: Since the Lions were the ones with a commanding lead, Riddick wasn't needed for his normal comeback mode role as the check-down option.  Matthew Stafford attempted just 26 passes on the day.  Riddick remains a basement-level RB3 in deeper PPR leagues as the Lions head into their bye.
report: Theo Riddick rushed three times for three yards and caught 2-of-3 targets for 20 yards in the Lions' Week 5 win over the Packers.

impact: The Lions ended Stafford's suffering with 8:15 left in the fourth quarter with the team trailing 48-17.  Stafford did not play well at all, but he didn't get a lot of help, with his offensive line whiffing on blocks, receivers dropping passes, and the running game again doing nothing.  Two of Stafford's picks went to ILB Darron Lee, and one of them was returned for a touchdown.  Stafford put together one impressive drive, marching 80 yards right down the field in 1:50 on four passes on the first drive of the third quarter, finishing it with a 24-yard touchdown to Golden Tate.  Stafford appeared to injure his left knee at one point, limping badly, and then also got the wind knocked out of him.  He missed one play.  Stafford will look to bounce back next week at the 49ers.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 27-of-46 passes for 286 yards, one touchdown, and four interceptions in the Lions' Week 1 loss to the Jets on Monday night.

impact: He was sacked twice for a loss of 18 yards and also lost a fumble. For Stafford, this was a much better game than his previous outing, a four-interception nightmare against the Jets on Monday Night Football. Though the numbers don’t really reflect it, Stafford still looked a tad off, continually airmailing deep balls downfield including one to a wide-open Marvin Jones that should have gone for an easy touchdown. Stafford did throw a touchdown to Jones later in the game, finding him for a five-yard score with 8:36 remaining in the fourth quarter. Stafford added another touchdown later in the fourth on a 15-yard end-zone heave to tight end Michael Roberts. The Lions made a valiant comeback in the second half but fell just short with Stafford’s fourth-down incompletion sealing the game with 14 seconds remaining. Stafford and the Lions will try to avoid falling to 0-3 next week against New England.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 34-of-53 passes for 347 yards and three touchdowns while adding one rush for eight yards Sunday in the Lions’ Week 2 loss to the 49ers.

impact: Stafford was sharp in this one, completing 12 of his first 13 passes. He played keep-away from the Patriots with clock killing drives. Stafford made a sidearm throw to Kenny Golladay in the red-zone for his first TD before hitting a wide open Marvin Jones from 33 yards out on his second. His only blunder was an interception on the opening drive of the second half. Stafford has rebounded from his rough Week 1 to post consecutive multi-TD games. He'll get a matchup with the Cowboys in Week 4.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 27-of-36 passes for 262 yards, two touchdowns, and an interception in Detroit's Week 3 win over the Patriots.

impact: Stafford was dropped three times for a loss of 21 yards. Playing in his hometown of Dallas, the former first overall pick impressed by going over the 300-yard barrier for the second time this season. Stafford made use of all his receivers but had his most success throwing to Golden Tate, who absorbed all eight of his targets for 132 yards and two touchdowns. His second score gave Detroit a one-point lead with a little over two minutes left in the fourth quarter, though the Cowboys wound up winning on a walk-off field goal by Brett Maher. Stafford and the Lions will hope to avoid falling to 1-4 when they face the Packers next week at Ford Field.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 24-of-30 passes for 307 yards and two touchdowns while adding five yards on two carries Sunday in the Lions’ Week 4 loss to Dallas.

impact: Detroit shocked Green Bay and jumped out to a big 24-0 halftime lead, so Stafford didn't have to do much of anything in the second half despite the Packers threatening a comeback before losing by eight.  Stafford threw just 11 second-half passes and watched LeGarrette Blount score a pair of short touchdowns before the break.  Kenny Golladay also had a 47-yard touchdown called back on a penalty, while Marvin Jones was unable to complete a diving catch on a 42-yard score.  The day could have been a lot bigger for Stafford.  The Lions are now on their bye week.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 14-of-26 passes for 183 yards and two touchdowns in the Lions' Week 5 win over the Packers.

impact: The Dolphins' secondary erased Stafford's elite receiver trio, but he compensated in fantasy by finding TE Michael Roberts for a pair of scores. The Lions rode their running game. No pass catcher drew more than six targets or posted more than 48 yards. Having a quiet roto campaign, Stafford will be a QB2 for Week 8 against the Seahawks' still-feisty defense.
report: Matthew Stafford completed 18-of-22 passes for 217 yards and two touchdowns in the Lions' 32-21, Week 7 win over the Dolphins.

impact: Griffin is not fantasy-relevant in an offense that doesn't feature its tight ends.
report: Ryan Griffin caught his lone target for 12 yards in the Texans' Week 4 win over the Colts.

impact: Griffin "exploded" for six catches and 65 yards against Dallas last week, but he could not build on the breakout here. It is unlikely he fares much better next week in Jacksonville.
report: Ryan Griffin did not catch any of his five targets Week 6 against the Bills.

impact: For the first time in a full game, Hunt was held without a reception. The Chiefs were playing from ahead but got dominated in time of possession and kept making big plays through the air. Hunt simply was not needed on the ground. Spencer Ware was involved behind him but only to the tune of four touches. Hunt should have a bounce-back effort in Week 2 against a Steelers run defense that has not been the same since Ryan Shazier went down.
report: Kareem Hunt rushed 16 times for 49 yards in the Chiefs' Week 1 win over the Chargers.

impact: Hunt was running with power, but he simply wasn't needed for a monster workload with Patrick Mahomes getting whatever he wanted through the air. The aggressive Mahomes has now found Hunt for just one catch through two games after Hunt averaged 3.5 receptions (throwing out a Week 17 cameo) last season. Hunt's ceiling remains sky-high in the Chiefs' high-voltage offense, but his weekly floor is going to be a little lower than it was as a rookie.
report: Kareem Hunt rushed 18 times for 75 yards in the Chiefs' Week 2 win over the Steelers, adding a five-yard touchdown reception.

impact: Hunt eased the minds of worried fantasy players with two one-yard touchdown runs in the first quarter, and he buoyed his fantasy game with 22 yards on a close-out drive in the fourth. There are still reasons for concern, however. He saw just one target, did not catch that pass, and sat out the two-minute drill at the end of the first half. He now has one catch through three games. Being attached to the best offense in the league should offer plenty of scoring chances, but the lack of receiving usage gives Hunt a concerning floor moving forward.
report: Kareem Hunt rushed 18 times for 44 yards and two touchdowns in the Chiefs' Week 3 win over the 49ers.

impact: Hunt added three catches for 54 yards on four targets.  In the first half, he was the focal point of the offense, as the Broncos' pass-rush and backend coverage made things difficult on Patrick Mahomes.  It's Hunt's first 100-yard rushing game of the season after six as a rookie.  Hunt was stuffed a couple times inside the five-yard line early before later cashing one in from four yards out late in the fourth quarter to cap the comeback and give the Chiefs a 26-23 lead.  Hunt will be a borderline RB1 next week at home against the stout Jaguars.
report: Kareem Hunt rushed 19 times for 121 yards and one touchdown in the Chiefs' 27-23, Week 4 win over the Broncos on Monday night.

impact: He added seven yards on one catch. Hunt understandably struggled to gain consistent yardage against a tough front, but he got loose for a 24-yard gain in the third quarter -- he cost the offense 15 yards with an unsportsmanlike penalty at the end of that carry -- and sealed the game with a four-yard touchdown run on the first play of the fourth. He padded his stats with 31 yards including a 15-yard gain on a drive deep into garbage time. Hunt now has five touchdowns in his last four games. He will be a solid RB1 next week in New England.
report: Kareem Hunt rushed 22 times for 87 yards and a touchdown in the Chiefs' Week 5 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Hunt lost some snaps to Spencer Ware with the Chiefs playing from behind early, but the Chiefs went back to him in the second half. He was left wide open on a third-and-short for a 67-yard TD to start the third quarter. Hunt should’ve had another touchdown but was stopped at the goal-line. After a slow start, Hunt’s been on fire over the last month, with at least 100 total yards or a touchdown in three straight games. He'll be an RB1 in Week 7 against the Bengals.
report: Kareem Hunt rushed 10 times for 80 yards and caught 5-of-6 passes for 105 yards and a touchdown in Week 6 against the Patriots.

impact: Hunt had one of the highlights of the year in this one, breaking multiple tackles and hurdling over a defender on a play that set up his first receiving touchdown. On his second, he took a red-zone dumpoff down the right sideline and extended over the pylon before going out of bounds. Hunt converted a goal-line carry for his rushing score on the Chiefs first drive of the second half. It's the second straight week Hunt's had an expanded pass game role after going over 100 yards receiving against the Patriots. Hunt has been on fire with a touchdown in five straight weeks. He'll remain a locked-in RB1 for Week 8 against Denver.
report: Kareem Hunt had 15 carries for 86 yards and a touchdown and caught 5-of-6 passes for 55 yards and two touchdowns in Week 7 against the Bengals.

impact: The Rams' tight ends are not usually involved in the offense, but that changed after both Brandin Cooks and Cooper Kupp left this game with concussions. Everett recorded all of his catches after Cooks left the game, and two of them came with Kupp out. He was also tackled at the one in the third quarter. If Cooks and Kupp are forced to sit, he could be a streaming option in deep two-tight end formats.
report: Gerald Everett hauled in all three of his targets for 24 yards in the Rams' Week 5 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Gerald Everett also got his first catch of the season in this one, taking a late target 17 yards. Despite Sean McVay's history, the tight end position has simply not been a focal point of the Rams' passing game. Neither player is worth rostering in redraft formats.
report: Tyler Higbee hauled in 1-of-2 targets for three yards and a touchdown in the Rams' Week 2 win over the Cardinals.

impact: The Rams other tight end Gerald Everett also had two targets against the Chargers. Higbee found the end zone last week against the Cardinals, but he's not worthy of a roster spot with just four targets on the year. Sean McVay will continue to ride Gurley, Cooks, Woods, and Kupp.
report: Tyler Higbee caught both of his targets for 35 yards in the Rams' Week 3 win over the Chargers.

impact: Higbee only practiced once this week, but he will give it a go on a bad knee. The Rams do not use their tight ends enough for Higbee to have any fantasy value. Los Angeles declared K Greg Zuerlein, KR/PR JoJo Natson, RB John Kelly, OLB Trevon Young, DT Sebastian Joseph-Day, and DT Tanzel Smart inactive for Week 5.
report: Rams TE Tyler Higbee (knee) is active for Week 5 against the Seahawks.

impact: One of Higbee's catches bounced off Cooper Kupp and into his hands for a 17-yard gain. He added another grab in the second quarter, but Gerald Everett was the tight end of choice in the second half. Normally the Rams do not heavily utilize Higbee's position, but that could change with both Brandin Cooks and Kupp dealing with concussions. Even so, Higbee is not even a good desperation option in standard formats.
report: Tyler Higbee hauled in 2-of-4 targets for 26 yards in the Rams' Week 5 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Running as the No. 2 for the Texans' undermanned receiver corps, Ellington's touchdown was just the sixth of his career. He will offer some desperation appeal for as long as Will Fuller (hamstring) is sidelined. The Texans get the Titans in Week 2.
report: Bruce Ellington caught 4-of-8 targets for 37 yards and a touchdown in the Texans' Week 1 loss to the Patriots.

impact: With Keke Coutee and Sammie Coates out, Ellington continued his run as Houston's clear-cut No. 3 receiver. Unfortunately, that position serves little to no value with Will Fuller (8-113-1) and DeAndre Hopkins (6-110-1) manning the outside. Coutee, who has a much higher ceiling than Ellington, should mix-in as the team's primary slot receiver once he's healthy.
report: Bruce Ellington caught all three of his targets for 45 yards in the Texans' Week 2 loss to the Titans.

impact: He's questionable to return. With Keke Coutee and Sammie Coates out, 	the Texans should go with tight heavy sets.
report: Bruce Ellington left Week 3 against the Giants with a hamstring injury.

impact: The only difference from Hooper's normal day is he caught a touchdown.  Otherwise, the yards and five targets are par for the course for him.  Hooper's score came from eight yards out.  When he scores, he's an obvious fantasy difference-maker, but those touchdowns are hard to predict.  For now, Hooper will remain a TE2 most weeks but has streamer appeal Week 3 against the Saints.
report: Austin Hooper caught all five of his targets for 59 yards and one touchdown in the Falcons' Week 2 win over the Panthers.

impact: It was a quiet afternoon for the Falcons tight end, though he did chip in with a two-point conversion following Tevin Coleman’s touchdown early in the fourth quarter. Hooper has only topped 30 yards once this season and won’t be an appealing streamer against the Bengals in Week 4.
report: Austin Hooper turned in three catches for 23 yards on four targets Sunday in Atlanta’s Week 3 loss to the Saints.

impact: Hooper went for 59 yards and a touchdown in Week 2, but he has predictably scuffled since, catching just four passes for 42 yards in two games. He did have an end-zone target in this game, and that usage makes him a touchdown-or-bust fantasy option.
report: Austin Hooper hauled in 1-of-2 targets for 19 yards in the Falcons' Week 4 loss to the Bengals.

impact: Under constant pressure, Matt Ryan was constantly checking down. That includes a first half "Hail Mary." The receptions were a new personal best while the yards were the third most of Hooper's career. Hooper might actually stay hot for Week 6, where the Falcons host the Bucs. No team has allowed more fantasy points to opposing tight ends.
report: Austin Hooper caught 9-of-12 targets for 77 yards in the Falcons' Week 5 loss to the Steelers.

impact: It is Hooper's second game in a row with nine catches after failing to top seven in any of his first 34 games. His touchdown came on a delay route where he was left wide open in the flat and stiffed armed a corner to the ground on his way into the end zone. He also came up with a big third-down conversion on the Falcons' final drive to help set up a field goal. With Calvin Ridley (ankle) and Mohamed Sanu (hip) questionable, Hooper will be a back-end TE1 next week.
report: Austin Hooper hauled in 9-of-10 targets for 71 yards and a touchdown in the Falcons' Week 6 win over the Bucs.

impact: Woods did not take advantage of his opportunities in the opener, but he rectified the problem against the Cardinals. He caught three passes for 30 yards in the first quarter, and he kept making plays the rest of the way. His fantasy day could have been much better, but Jared Goff missed him when he was wide open in the end zone in the fourth. The Rams will have a tougher time with the Chargers next week, but Woods will still be a solid WR3.
report: Robert Woods hauled in 6-of-9 targets for 81 yards in the Rams' Week 2 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Going into the game, Woods was a breakout candidate as he was leading the team in targets and air yards but only had 118 scoreless yards to show for it. Today was a different story. The Chargers had no answers for Jared Goff and Woods, who scored two times on the same red zone play and ended with over 100 receiving yards. With at least nine targets in all three games, Woods is a WR2/3 even against the Vikings on Thursday night.
report: Robert Woods caught 10-of-11 targets for 104 yards and two touchdowns in the Rams' Week 3 win over the Chargers.

impact: With both Brandin Cooks and Cooper Kupp sidelined by concussions, Woods was the No. 1 receiver for most of this game, and he delivered. He made a great move after the catch to pick up third down and a lot more in the second quarter, and he sparked a touchdown drive with a 56-yard gain on a jet sweep in the third quarter. He drew a defensive pass interference on fourth down later that drive to keep it alive. Woods now has at least 100 yards from scrimmage in each of his last three games while Cooks and Kupp are question marks for next week. If they do not play, Woods will be a WR1 against the Broncos.
report: Robert Woods hauled in 5-of-7 targets for 92 yards and rushed twice for 53 yards in the Rams' Week 5 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Woods also drew an end zone DPI that set the Rams up at the one-yard line in the third quarter. With Cooper Kupp (knee) ailing, Woods gobbled up more than half of the Rams' receiving yards. Woods has now cleared 90 yards in four-straight games, and 100 in three of his past four. He's been operating as a poor man's Adam Thielen in the Rams' three-headed attack at wideout. The 49ers are a plus matchup for Week 7.
report: Robert Woods caught 7-of-10 targets for 109 yards in the Rams' Week 6 win over the Broncos, adding a 12-yard rush.

impact: The Rams' passing attack did not have to do much in the easy win, but Woods still managed to top 75 for the sixth game in a row. He helped set up a field goal with a 21-yard gain on third down in the first quarter, and he went for 32 yards to spark another scoring drive in the second. With the Packers likely to offer more resistance, Woods will once again be a high-end WR2 next week.
report: Robert Woods hauled in 5-of-7 targets for 78 yards in the Rams' Week 7 win over the 49ers.

impact: Both targets came with Dallas playing from behind in the second half. The fact that Thompson, a 29-year-old, undrafted journeyman, is playing significant snaps shows how desperate the Cowboys are for pass-catching help. Thompson can be left on the waiver wire for next week’s matchup against the Lions.
report: Deonte Thompson nabbed both of his targets for 23 yards Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 3 loss to Seattle.

impact: Snead didn't make much noise in the preseason, but he worked as the clear No. 3 wideout behind Michael Crabtree and John Brown. His role looks larger than expected in Baltimore's offense, but this may end up one of his better games. Playing on a short week, Snead would be a low-upside waiver-wire flyer.
report: Willie Snead caught 4-of-6 targets for 49 yards and a touchdown in Baltimore's Week 1 win over Buffalo.

impact: This was actually Snead's worst game of the season, but he still managed a couple big plays including a third-down conversion in the third quarter. Snead does not offer much upside as the No. 3 option in the passing game, but he can provide value in deeper PPR leagues.
report: Willie Snead hauled in 3-of-5 targets for 39 yards in the Ravens' Week 3 win over the Broncos.

impact: Snead was fourth on the team in targets as he's established himself as the possession receiver for the Ravens. Snead has four or more catches in four of five games this season, but has yet to reach 60-yards in any game to this point. The Ravens play at Tennessee in Week 6.
report: Willie Snead caught 5-of-7 targets for 55 yards in Sunday's Week 5 loss to the Browns.

impact: His catches and targets were both team-highs, with Michael Crabtree (6/93/1) leading the Ravens with 93 receiving yards. Snead has established himself as the club's possession wideout, but even finished with the second-most air yards (123) among Baltimore's receivers Sunday. It was all at the expense of John Brown, who recorded just two catches for 23 yards. Crabtree and Brown will still rank higher in Week 7 against the Saints.
report: Willie Snead hauled in a team-high 7-of-10 targets for 60 yards in the Ravens' Week 6 victory over the Titans.

impact: Amazingly, this was Snead's worst game of the season. He's averaging a solid 48 weekly yards but not really doing much with them in the way of catches or scores. He hasn't found the end zone since Week 1. Snead is just a desperation PPR fill-in.
report: Willie Snead caught 3-of-7 targets for 23 yards in the Ravens' Week 7 loss to the Saints.

impact: He was in on just nine-of-59 offensive snaps (15.3 percent). It would probably take an injury to one of the Cowboys starters for Williams to have any real fantasy relevance, and even then, that might be a stretch.
report: Terrance Williams wasn’t targeted Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 3 loss to the Seahawks.

impact: Heuerman was hardly heard from despite the Broncos teeing up a season-high 51 pass attempts, which is concerning for Heuerman's streamer viability going forward.  He will be a low-end TE2 in Week 6 against the Rams.
report: Jeff Heuerman caught 2-of-4 targets for 18 yards in the Broncos' Week 5 loss.

impact: The yards were Heuerman's second most of the season. He's done little to suggest he will be anything more than a last-gasp TE2 in fantasy leagues.
report: Jeff Heuerman caught 3-of-6 targets for 23 yards in the Broncos' Week 6 loss to the Rams.

impact: Blue was out-touched 21-5 in the Texans' season opener but closed the gap (16-7) in Week 2. Miller is still being used as an every-down workhorse, but he admittedly lacks explosiveness and hasn't shown a propensity to break tackles yet this season. Until Blue eats into Miller's opportunities, though, it's the latter who's still the back to own in Houston.
report: Alfred Blue rushed seven times for 36 yards in the Texans' Week 2 loss to the Titans.

impact: Meanwhile, Lamar Miller rushed 15 times for 49 yards, so neither runner had much success.  Blue was targeted three times in the pass game, catching none of them.  The 15-12 touch share is a bit concerning for Miller owners.
report: Alfred Blue rushed 12 times for 31 yards in the Texans' Week 4 win over the Colts.

impact: Blue started and had a workhorse role despite Lamar Miller (chest) being active. He was more of a factor in the passing game, but Blue had some nice runs. The Texans never let Blue get in a rhythm and he was passed over for multiple goal-line looks in favor of Deshaun Watson. Miller was close to playing this week, so Blue will likely return to a backup role in Week 6.
report: Alfred Blue rushed 20 times for 46 yards and caught eight passes for 73 yards in Week 5 against the Cowboys.

impact: With Lamar Miller back, Blue went right back into a secondary role against the Bills. He did flash with a 17-yard run early, but he was mostly held in check the rest of the way. D'Onta Foreman's potential return is a concern for Blue's handcuff value moving forward.
report: Alfred Blue rushed seven times for 26 yards and caught 2-of-3 targets for 17 yards in the Texans' Week 6 win over the Bills.

impact: He added five carries for 19 yards on the ground. Prescott didn't turn the ball over, but he also didn't throw a single touchdown. It's the seventh time in his last nine games that Prescott has failed to eclipse the 200-yard mark. Although Dak shoulders the blame as quarterback, rookie LG Connor Williams was as advertised (and not in a good way) in pass-protection and OC Scott Linehan could not have taken a more vanilla approach to Sunday's gameplan. It's early, but Prescott's ceiling may be lower than initially thought if slot receiver Cole Beasley continues being his clear-cut target in the flats.
report: Dak Prescott completed 19-of-29 passes for 170 yards in the Cowboys' Week 1 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Prescott wasn't asked to do much with the Cowboys defense shutting down the Giants. His touchdown was a 64-yard catch and run by Tavon Austin on the third play of the night. Prescott managed the game after that, but he added 45 yards on seven rushes. Through two weeks, Prescott has looked like the quarterback he was in the second half of last year. He gets a matchup with Seattle in Week 3.
report: Dak Prescott completed 16-of-25 passes for 160 yards and a touchdown in Week 2 against the Giants.

impact: Dak took five sacks for a loss of 31 yards. Plagued by a patchwork receiving corps and a declining offensive line, Prescott limped to just 40 yards on 6-of-13 passing in the first half. He was only marginally better after the break and spent much of his day trying to escape Frank Clark, who dominated up front for Seattle. Prescott’s lone touchdown "pass" came on a shovel throw to Tavon Austin with 7:11 left in the fourth quarter. Any chance of a late comeback ended when Earl Thomas pulled in his second interception of the day on a pass intended for Blake Jarwin. Perhaps Prescott will fare better against an attackable Lions defense at home next week, but with the Cowboys’ offense struggling in all facets, Dak will be little more than a back-end QB2 in fantasy.
report: Dak Prescott completed 19-of-34 passes for 168 yards with a touchdown and two interceptions while adding 21 yards on two carries Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 3 loss to Seattle.

impact: Prescott lost 24 yards on three sacks in the victory. Sunday marked Dak's first 200-yard passing game since Week 15 of last season. He spread the wealth, targeting eight different receivers including Ezekiel Elliott, who led the way with 88 yards and a touchdown on four catches. Prescott's first touchdown of the afternoon came on a screen to Zeke, who took it 38 yards to the house late in the second quarter. Dak later found tight end Geoff Swaim for a one-yard touchdown off a play-action pass, which stretched the Cowboys lead to 10 with under three minutes to go in the third quarter. That lead would evaporate but Dak kept his poise down the stretch, leading a late-scoring drive keyed by a 34-yard completion to Elliott down the right sideline. This was easily Prescott's best outing of 2018, which admittedly wasn't a high bar to clear after struggling mightily in his first three games. We'll see if he can build off this performance next week at Houston.
report: Dak Prescott completed 17-of-27 passes for 255 yards and two touchdowns while adding two yards on three carries Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 4 victory over the Lions.

impact: Prescott’s struggles resurfaced coming off his best game in Week 5. Both of his interceptions were on dropped passes, but Prescott was off the mark on the throws.  Prescott somewhat salvaged his night with 36 yards rushing. He doesn't have much of a supporting cast, but it's clear Prescott has regressed from last year. Prescott will be a back-end QB2 for a tough Week 6 matchup with Jacksonville.
report: Dak Prescott completed 18-of-29 passes for 208 yards with a touchdown and two interceptions in the Cowboys' Week 5 loss to the Texans.

impact: He lost 11 yards on three sacks in the victory. Going against arguably the league's toughest defense, Dak didn't blink, making Jacksonville pay for ignoring slot receiver Cole Beasley (nine catches for 101 yards and two touchdowns). Prescott also had a good day running the football, breaking out for a career-high 82 yards with a long gain of 28 yards. He probably would have had a bigger day had the score been closer but with Dallas winning big, Prescott only attempted nine passes after halftime. Next the Cowboys head to Washington for a division showdown against the Redskins in Week 7.
report: Dak Prescott completed 17-of-27 passes for 183 yards and two touchdowns while adding 82 yards and another touchdown on 11 rushes Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 6 victory over Jacksonville.

impact: Prescott ate a shoulder pad directly to his helmet while sliding near the sideline early in the first half, which forced Dallas' training staff to bring out the blue medical tent. He was cleared soon after with what was comically declared as a 'hand' injury. Prescott did encouragingly keep to his running ways, though, recording six carries for the third consecutive game. He's now averaged 7.6 rushes, 49.6 rushing yards, and 0.6 rushing touchdowns in the last three games for Dallas. Prescott will return from the Cowboys' Week 8 bye as a sneaky streaming QB2 versus the Titans.
report: Dak Prescott completed 22-of-35 passes for 273 yards and one touchdown, chipping in another 33 yards and one score on the ground in the Cowboys' Week 7 loss to the Redskins.

impact: White had not caught a pass coming into this game, but he got a bit more run with Allen Robinson hobbled by a groin injury. That playing time almost led to a spectacular moment when White came down with the potential game-tying Hail Mary on the final play of the game, but he made the catch just short of the goal line and was pushed back by a group of defenders. Despite the big play and Robinson's injury, White is not a fantasy option.
report: Kevin White hauled in both of his targets for 64 yards in the Bears' Week 7 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Filling in for Brandin Cooks and Cooper Kupp, who both left the game with concussions, Reynolds came out hot following halftime. He had a 22-yard catch on the second offensive play of the half, a 17-yard grab the next play, and he rushed for 10 yards the play after that. He did not touch the ball again the rest of the game, but Reynolds is a talented young receiver who might be forced into playing time with Cooks and Kupp questionable. He should be added in most formats.
report: Josh Reynolds hauled in 2-of-3 targets for 39 yards and rushed once for 10 yards in the Rams' Week 5 win over the Seahawks.

impact: The story of Reynolds' Week 6 was Cooper Kupp's knee injury. It appeared Kupp's season was over before he miraculously returned for the second half (and barely played). Provided Kupp continues to get good news, Reynolds will remain on the outside looking in of fantasy value for Week 7 against the 49ers.
report: Josh Reynolds caught 1-of-2 targets for -2 yards in the Rams' Week 6 win over the Broncos.

impact: Even with Cooper Kupp sidelined, Reynolds did not see a big boost. He did set up a touchdown with a 19-yard catch down to the one-yard line in the third quarter, but that was his only involvement. Even with uncertainty about Kupp’s availability, Reynolds can be sent back to the wire.
report: Josh Reynolds caught his only target for 19 yards in the Rams' Week 7 win over the 49ers.

impact: His total rushing yards were nice, but Zeke ultimately fell victim to OC Scott Linehan's mundane early-down rushing scheme behind an offensive line missing C Travis Frederick in the middle. He handled 15 of Dallas' 17 backfield carries, though, reassuring his bell-cow status. Zeke will have to overcome loaded boxes with all the touches he's bound to receive if he's going to finish as a top-three back.
report: Ezekiel Elliott rushed for 69 yards and one score on 15 carries while adding three catches for 17 yards on four targets in the Cowboys’ Week 1 loss to the Panthers.

impact: Elliott had a quiet night before scoring a six-yard fourth quarter touchdown. He was the Cowboys entire offense aside from a 64-yard Tavon Austin touchdown on the third play of the night. Despite playing behind an offensive line missing Travis Frederick, Elliott has managed 80 total yards and a touchdown in both games to start the year. He'll remain a locked-in top-five option for Week 3 against Seattle.
report: Ezekiel Elliott rushed 17 times for 78 yards and a touchdown and caught 5-of-6 passes for nine yards in the Cowboys' Week 2 win over the Giants on Sunday night.

impact: After opening the year with a pair of so-so games, Elliott played legitimately well on Sunday, particularly in the second half when he broke loose for 76 yards on only seven carries. Zeke’s longest gain came on a 26-yard burst in the fourth quarter, though Bradley McDougald spoiled it by stripping him at the end of his run, resulting in a turnover. Elliott has averaged 16 carries per game this year, which is well below the 24.2 he averaged last season. We’ll see what the 23-year-old can cobble up next week against the Lions.
report: Ezekiel Elliott totaled 127 yards on 16 carries while securing three-of-eight targets for 11 yards Sunday in the Cowboys’ Week 3 loss to the Seahawks.
