impact: Zeke's 240 yards from scrimmage—140 of which came after halftime—set a career-high. Elliott was, for large stretches of the afternoon, the Cowboys' only source of offense. The third-year back got to stepping with a 38-yard touchdown off a screen pass late in the second quarter. He rumbled to a 41-yard run, his longest of the game, in the third quarter. Elliott made arguably his biggest contribution when he hauled in a 34-yard deep bomb from Dak Prescott, putting the Cowboys in field-goal range with under two minutes left in the fourth quarter. The Cowboys' offensive line has mostly struggled this year, but they went all out for Zeke in Week 4. Elliott, who currently leads the NFL with 426 rushing yards, will look to stay hot when he faces the Texans next week on Sunday Night Football.
report: Ezekiel Elliott exploded for 152 yards on 25 carries while also contributing four catches for a team-high 88 yards and a touchdown Sunday in Dallas’ Week 4 win over the Lions.

impact: Coming off a brutal outing against Houston in Week 5 (54 yards on 21 carries), Zeke was much better Sunday, shredding the Jags for 61 rushing yards in the second half. Elliott tallied his fourth touchdown of the year on a 15-yard scamper early in the fourth quarter. The Cowboys' offense isn't what it was a few years ago but Elliott has remained productive, leading the NFL with 586 rushing yards through six games. Even with his clunker against the Texans, Zeke has still cleared 100 yards rushing in three of his last four contests. He'll look to make it four out of five when he takes on the Redskins in Week 7.
report: Ezekiel Elliott rumbled to 106 yards and a touchdown on 24 carries while gaining 11 yards on his lone catch Sunday in Dallas’ Week 6 win over the Jaguars.

impact: Washington's defense kept Elliott bottled at the line of scrimmage, permitting just 2.2 YPC. He was in position to score on the goal line late in the fourth quarter, but Dak Prescott kept the ball and scampered over the middle and crossed the plain himself instead. Although his six targets were encouraging, it's the second straight week Zeke has been held under 12 yards receiving, and already the fourth time he's failed to reach that mark this season. His on-field usage and involvement remains that of a true bell-cow, though, keeping him as a weekly top-five option despite porous results in Dallas' passing game. The Cowboys are on bye in Week 8.
report: Ezekiel Elliott handled 15 carries for 34 yards, tacking on two catches for the nine yards in the Cowboys' Week 7 loss to the Redskins.

impact: Allen continues to struggle to produce positive yardage -- he now has 32 yards on 16 carries this season -- but he also continues to find the end zone. His first score came on a 12-yard pass in which he was able to get the corner and dive for the pylon, and he added a one-yard rushing touchdown in the third quarter. He is going to offer next to nothing when he fails to score, but Allen is a weekly FLEX consideration because of his red-zone role.
report: Javorius Allen rushed six times for seven yards and a touchdown and caught three passes for 19 yards and another score in the Ravens' Week 3 win over the Broncos.

impact: Allen played ahead of Alex Collins for most of the second quarter after Collins lost a goal-line fumble. He didn't have any highlights, but his workloads have been trending up. Allen will be a touchdown-dependent FLEX for Week 5 against the Browns.
report: Javorius Allen rushed 10 times for 30 yards and caught two passes for 17 yards in Week 4 against the Steelers.

impact: Allen also lost a fumble on one his six catches. He out-touched Alex Collins 14-to-13 and once again entered the game for goal line opportunities, though he failed to convert. Allen has at worst forced a committee with Collins and has a firm grasp on receiving work in the Baltimore offense. He's arguably a safer fantasy option at this stage since he is siphoning goal line snaps. Allen will enter Week 6 as an RB2/FLEX option against the Titans with a larger boost in PPR formats.
report: Javorius Allen rushed eight times for 34 yards while catching 6-of-8 targets for 44 yards in Sunday's Week 5 loss to the Browns.

impact: Only one week after out-touching (14-13) and out-snapping (50-27) teammate Alex Collins, Allen fell victim to Baltimore's early lead and ensuing run-heavy game script. Collins inevitably out-carried Buck 19-1 on the day. In a closer game, perhaps Allen would've been used more, but his week-to-week usage is a legitimate dice roll at this point given coach Jon Harbaugh's recent statement about just "keeping Collins fresh." Allen has a higher floor (and will be needed) as the team's only pass-catching back in Week 7 against the Saints.
report: Javorius Allen rushed just one time for one yard and caught all three of his targets for 18 yards in the Ravens' Week 6 mauling of the Titans.

impact: Allen has four carries for four yards over his past two games. Alex Collins is hardly setting the world on fire, but Allen is not making a meaningful push for more work. Allen is a bottom-of-the-barrel, bye week fill-in RB3. The Ravens get the Panthers in Week 8.
report: Javorius Allen rushed three times for three yards in the Ravens' Week 7 loss to the Saints, adding three receptions for 21 additional yards.

impact: He caught all four of his targets for 18 additional yards.  With Devonta Freeman (knee) out, Coleman got his 20 touches, while rookie RB Ito Smith chipped in with 55 yards on 10 touches.  Coleman's bug run went for 36 yards, and he also had a 19-yarder that was very close to going to the house for a long touchdown.  Coleman was unable to convert his run inside the 10-yard line for a score, getting it down to the one before Matt Ryan scored on a sneak the next play.  With Freeman expected to miss at least another game, Coleman will be an upside RB2 next week against New Orleans.
report: Tevin Coleman rushed 16 times for 107 yards in the Falcons' 31-24, Week 2 win over the Panthers.

impact: Starting for the second straight week, Coleman spent most of the afternoon running into brick walls, though he salvaged the day for fantasy owners with a late receiving touchdown. Coleman broke through for a 15-yard gain on his first touch of the second half but averaged a pathetic 1.29 yards on his other 14 carries. The 25-year-old also committed a costly mistake on the Falcons’ final drive, failing to pick up a blitz that resulted in a Matt Ryan incompletion on third down. He’ll look to redeem himself next week against Cincinnati.
report: Tevin Coleman netted just 33 yards on 15 carries while delivering two catches for 14 yards and a touchdown on three targets Sunday in the Falcons’ Week 3 loss to New Orleans.

impact: Coleman looked good when he got the touches in this game and appeared on the cusp of breaking a few long gains. Unfortunately, he ceded 10 touches to Ito Smith including what became a seven-yard touchdown on the opening drive. With Devonta Freeman looking likely to return next week, Coleman will return to the RB3/FLEX mix against the Steelers.
report: Tevin Coleman rushed 14 times for 51 yards and hauled in all three of his targets for 26 yards in the Falcons' Week 4 loss to the Bengals.

impact: Devonta Freeman started and won the touch battle, but Coleman played just one fewer snap. Ito Smith was also involved as the No. 3 back. Despite the disappointing day and the Falcons' increasingly crowded backfield, Coleman will have Week 6 FLEX appeal against the Bucs' horrific defense.
report: Tevin Coleman rushed seven times for 15 yards in the Falcons' Week 5 loss to the Steelers, adding two receptions for 15 additional yards.

impact: Coleman looked like he was going to disappoint fantasy players for most of this game. He failed to create any big plays on the ground, and he lost 11 carries and a touchdown to Ito Smith. Thankfully, he saved his fantasy day with a six-yard touchdown catch in the fourth quarter. Coleman remains a starter any time Freeman sits, but Smith's involvement means he will be more of an RB2 moving forward.
report: Tevin Coleman rushed 10 times for 35 yards and hauled in 1-of-2 targets for six yards and a touchdown in the Falcons' Week 6 win over the Bucs.

impact: He added 32 yards through the air by catching both of his targets.  Coleman started the night off with a 14-yard run and ended it with a 30-yard touchdown run where he went untouched through the right side.  He lives off big plays and hasn't been making many of them this season.  But Coleman out-played Ito Smith by a wide margin, out-gaining him 82-45 on four more touches.  Coleman gets a bye and will remain an RB2 in Week 9 against the Redskins.
report: Tevin Coleman rushed 11 times for 50 yards and one touchdown in the Falcons' Week 7 win over the Giants.

impact: Todd Gurley was dealing with cramps, so Brown got all the work in the fourth quarter. He played well and seems like he would be a reliable starter if something were to happen to Gurley. The Rams also have rookie John Kelly, who has been inactive the first two weeks.
report: Malcolm Brown rushed 12 times for 46 yards in the Rams' Week 2 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Rookie John Kelly was a healthy scratch for the third straight week meaning Malcolm Brown is the handcuff to Todd Gurley. With Gurley healthy, Brown is solely a change-of-pace back for the Rams, and he can't be started in fantasy.
report: Malcolm Brown rushed five times for 42 yards in the Rams' Week 3 win over the Chargers.

impact: This was Cohen's best game of the season after he posted just 66 total yards on 14 touches through the opening two games. The downside is that Cohen is still just being used a spell-back and not a player the Bears are scheming as a large part of their offense. With Jordan Howard as a true workhorse, Cohen needs more consistent passing-game involvement to be considered a fantasy option moving forward.
report: Tarik Cohen rushed five times for 53 yards while catching all three of his targets for 15 yards in Sunday's Week 3 win over the Cardinals.

impact: This type of performance was always in Cohen's range of outcomes. What really stood out, though, was that Cohen out-touched Jordan Howard 20-11 and was involved early and often in the Bears' offensive game plan. Not only did he lead the club in targets, Cohen also led Chicago's backfield in carries, getting involved well before the offense erupted for a 38-3 lead heading into the half. It was admittedly a day where everything just went right for the Bears, led by Mitchell Trubisky's career-high six touchdown tosses. Everything seems to be clicking for Chicago heading into the team's Week 5 bye, and better days seem to be ahead for Cohen if kept involved. If you were thinking about dropping him, that's no longer an option.
report: Tarik Cohen rushed 13 times for 53 yards while corralling 7-of-8 targets for 121 yards and one touchdown in Sunday's Week 4 win over the Bucs.

impact: He saw two fewer touches than backfield-mate Jordan Howard (14-12) but out-gained him by over 50 yards. Cohen flashed his signature speed with a number of big plays including a 21-yard touchdown burst during the third quarter. He added a 50-yard catch-and-run later in the half and nearly scored a second touchdown, but it was called back on offensive pass interference. Cohen did hit a few rough patches, getting stuffed on a fourth-and-one opportunity and also losing a fumble in Bears territory late in the second half. After playing second fiddle early in the year, Cohen has pulled even with Howard in Chicago's backfield pecking order. Look for their timeshare to continue next week against New England.
report: Tarik Cohen contributed 31 yards and a touchdown on five carries while adding seven catches for 90 yards on nine targets Sunday in the Bears’ Week 6 loss to the Dolphins.

impact: Following a disappointing start to the season, Cohen has established himself as a big part of Chicago’s offense, and that continued in this one. Cohen finished the first half with just one fewer touch than Jordan Howard, although that total was boosted by two catches with less than 10 seconds left in the half, and dominated work after the break. He started strong in the second half, catching a six-yard touchdown on the opening drive, and he added six more catches to his total after halftime. He now has at least seven catches in each of his last three games. He will be a great PPR option and an RB3/FLEX in standard formats next week against the Jets.
report: Tarik Cohen rushed six times for 14 yards and hauled in 8-of-12 targets for 69 yards and a touchdown in the Bears' Week 7 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Despite sitting out all of the fourth quarter due to cramps, Gurley did his fantasy backers right in the blowout win. He scored three times from short distance, and he backed up two of those scores with two-point conversions. Completely healthy -- Gurley was walking around the sidelines in the fourth and almost certainly would have reentered the game if not for the score -- Gurley will be the top overall running back option next week against the Chargers.
report: Todd Gurley rushed 19 times for 42 yards and three touchdowns and caught all three of his targets for 31 yards in the Rams' Week 2 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Gurley now has at least 19 carries in all three games. As he usually does, Gurley converted a goal line carry for his fourth touchdown of the year. With a 28-13 lead in the third quarter, Gurley was fed carries and the Chargers were unable to stop him. Through three games, Gurley is averaging 25.5 PPR points and will remain an elite RB1 against the Vikings on Thursday night.
report: Todd Gurley rushed 23 times for 105 yards and one touchdown and caught five passes for 51 yards in the Rams' Week 3 win over the Chargers.

impact: Gurley averaged just 3.5 yards per carry, but that does not matter on a day he scores three times. The first two came from two yards out, and the third was a five-yarder in the fourth quarter. Gurley almost had a fourth score, but he was ruled down at the one and then stuffed at the goal line on the next play in the second quarter. Gurley now had at least one score in every game and two three-touchdown performances in just five games. He will remain the overall RB1 next week in Denver.
report: Todd Gurley rushed 22 times for 77 yards and three touchdowns while catching 4-of-5 targets for 36 yards in the Rams' Week 5 win over the Seahawks.

impact: One week after Isaiah Crowell demolished the Broncos' crumbling run defense, Gurley wrecked it for a new career high in rushing yards. Gurley was ripping chunk gains essentially every time he touched the ball, averaging 7.42 yards per carry. For the season, Gurley's YPC now rests at 4.82, while he's scored 11 total touchdowns, putting him on pace for 29. Gurley should run all over the 49ers, who will be playing on a short week, in Week 7.
report: Todd Gurley rushed 28 times for 208 yards and a pair of touchdowns in the Rams' Week 6 win over the Broncos, adding two receptions for 17 additional yards.

impact: He scored a touchdown because that is what he does, but Gurley was mostly held in check in the first half. That changed in the third quarter when he went for nine and 18 yards on back-to-back carries, and he managed to find the end zone again from one yard out later that quarter. Following a long punt return, he ended his day and any doubt about the outcome of the game with a 12-yard touchdown catch on a screen pass in the fourth. That score gave Gurley 14 for the season and tied him with Priest Holmes for the most touchdowns through seven games in NFL history. He now has three games with three touchdowns this season and eight total the last three weeks. He will look to keep things going next week against the Packers.
report: Todd Gurley rushed 15 times for 63 yards and two touchdowns and caught 4-of-5 targets for 23 yards and another score in the Rams' Week 7 win over the 49ers.

impact: Booker operated as the third-down back early in the game and saw passing-down work all day, but he appeared to fall down the depth chart in this one. Following a 29-yard touchdown catch in the first quarter, Phillip Lindsay worked as the No. 2 running back and even matched Royce Freeman in rushing attempts and yards. Looking like the third option in a committee backfield, Booker does not need to be rostered in standard-sized redraft leagues.
report: Devontae Booker rushed twice for four yards and hauled in both his targets for 11 yards in the Broncos' Week 1 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Denver's No. 3 back, Booker took on a bigger role in the second half after Phillip Lindsay was ejected just before halftime. He did not do much with it, and he should fall back behind Lindsay in the pecking order next week.
report: Devontae Booker hauled in 5-of-7 targets for 34 yards and rushed five times for 10 yards in the Broncos' Week 3 loss to the Ravens.

impact: He remains the third wheel in Denver's backfield, but still an active one.  And Booker's activity spiked a bit this week because the Broncos got destroyed by the Jets and played passing-game specialist Booker more than usual.  Booker would still need a Phillip Lindsay or Royce Freeman injury to become a legit flex option, but he is worth stashing in 14- and 16-team PPR leagues.
report: Devontae Booker caught 5-of-6 targets for 59 yards in the Broncos' Week 5 loss to the Jets.

impact: The only thing not to like about Goff’s performance was he only threw one touchdown. He probably should have had two more, but he underthrew Brandin Cooks, who had to come back to the ball and the defender, and missed a wide-open Robert Woods in the end zone. Neither play ultimately mattered in a game the Rams won going away. Goff might need to be sharper next week against the Chargers, though.
report: Jared Goff completed 24-of-32 passes for 354 yards, a touchdown, and an interception in the Rams' Week 2 win over the Cardinals.

impact: Goff has back-to-back games with 354 passing yards, but his three touchdowns are the most since Week 15 of 2017. Robert Woods was Goff's primary target today as the two connected for two touchdowns, but Brandin Cooks came just one foot short of his first touchdown too. Sean McVay has this offense cooking right now -- they have scored at least 33 points in all three games -- but they have a test with the Vikings coming up on Thursday Night Football.
report: Jared Goff completed 29-of-36 passes for 354 yards, three touchdowns, and an interception in the Rams' Week 3 win over the Chargers.

impact: It was not pretty, but Goff helped lead the Rams to a 5-0 start with three scoring drives in the second half and some timely plays, most notably a fourth-down conversion on a sneak to ice the game late in the fourth quarter. Goff's first interception was a forced throw which was tipped into the air at the goal line, but the second came on a Hail Mary at the end of the first half. That said, he probably deserved at least two interceptions and got lucky on several throws. Goff could have had another score, but Todd Gurley was ruled down at the one on a jet shovel pass in the second quarter. Goff has now thrown for at least 320 yards in four straight games. He will be a back-end QB1 next week in Denver.
report: Jared Goff completed 23-of-32 passes for 321 yards, a touchdown, and two interceptions in the Rams' Week 5 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Goff had his first scoreless start of the season as the Rams gutted the Broncos on the ground. He now has just one touchdown and three picks over his past two starts, both Rams victories. Today's giveaway came on a twice-tipped pass. There has been little overt reason for alarm. It just seems to be the normal ebbs and flows of a fantasy campaign. Goff nearly received some awful news this afternoon when Cooper Kupp appeared to shred his knee, but he miraculously returned after the break. Goff will remain a locked-in QB1 for Week 7 against the 49ers.
report: Jared Goff completed 14-of-28 passes for 201 yards, zero touchdowns and an interception in the Rams' 23-20, Week 6 win over the Broncos.

impact: With the 49ers turning it over for fun, Goff did not have to do much in this one. He still managed a respectable fantasy outing with two touchdowns. The first came on a great route by Brandin Cooks in the second quarter, and the second was on a screen pass to Todd Gurley in the fourth. After a hot run, Goff has now thrown for just 403 yards and two scores total in his last two games. He should fare better next week against the Packers.
report: Jared Goff completed 18-of-24 passes for 202 yards and two touchdowns in the Rams' Week 7 win over the 49ers.

impact: Trubisky had a solid first half before fizzling over the final two quarters. His only touchdown was a designed run at the goal-line, with the rest of his rushng coming on broken play scrambles. Trubisky had a good rapport with Allen Robinson, who lead the team in receiving. It's a step in the right direction for Trubisky after a rough rookie season, but there's not a ton to get excited about with his Year 2 outlook.
report: Mitchell Trubisky completed 23-of-35 passes for 171 yards in Sunday night's Week 1 loss to the Packers, adding seven carries for 32 yards and a rushing touchdown.

impact: It's been a disgusting start to the season for the sophomore, who is averaging a pitiful 5.4 YPA on his first 69 attempts.  Only Sam Bradford's 4.0 YPA mark has been worse among qualified quarterbacks.  Trubisky should have had a third interception in the end zone at the end of the first half, but CB Justin Coleman flat-out dropped it.  Trubisky's first pick was a terribly underthrown sideline shot to Allen Robinson, while the other was a ball batted at the line of scrimmage.  The touchdowns were a three-yard shovel pass to Trey Burton and an off-balance, 10-yarder to Anthony Miller.  Trubisky flashes upside at rare times but mostly plays wildly inaccurate with a tendency to run.  He's one of the worst fantasy quarterbacks and won't be on the radar next week in Arizona, even against that horrendous defense.
report: Mitchell Trubisky completed 25-of-34 passes for 200 yards, two touchdowns, and two interceptions in the Bears' Week 2 win over the Seahawks.

impact: Trubisky also rushed twice for eight yards, losing a fumble on a scramble. He played with fire on multiple occasions, throwing a few would-be interceptions had defenders secured the ball. Trubisky has now averaged just 5.7 yards per pass attempt through three games and has struggled to connect on anything down the field. The silver lining is that his yards per pass attempt have risen in each game, but Trubisky and the Bears are indeed not the second coming of Sean McVay and Jared Goff if the opening three weeks are any indication of the rest of the season.
report: Mitchell Trubisky completed 24-of-35 passes for 220 yards with one interception in Sunday's Week 3 win over the Cardinals.

impact: He also led the team with 53 yards rushing. Trubisky came only one-score short of tying the NFL record for most touchdown passes in a single game. It was the perfect storm for the second-year pro, who not only found milk carton candidates Trey Burton (2-86-1) and Tarik Cohen (7-121-1 receiving), but who was also helped by the Bucs' ineptitude on defense. Even Taylor Gabriel was involved in Chicago's efforts Sunday, recording a career-high 104 receiving yards and two scores. This can't possibly be expected from Trubisky moving forward, but it's certainly a positive that his yards per attempt have increased in every outing this season. Matt Nagy's offense should continue developing and clicking against the Dolphins after the bye.
report: Mitchell Trubisky completed 19-of-26 passes for 354 yards and six touchdowns in the Bears' Week 4 win over the Buccaneers.

impact: He was dropped for two sacks, which resulted in a loss of 13 yards. Trubisky has now thrown for nine touchdown passes over his last two outings, the same number he had in his first 15 starts. The 2017 first-rounder did almost all of his damage after halftime, throwing for 222 yards on 12-of-16 passing in the second half. Trubisky was far from perfect—he was bailed out on a handful of spectacular catches (the most absurd of the bunch coming on a 47-yard deep heave to Taylor Gabriel in the second quarter) and was intercepted in the end zone on a pass he never should have thrown. But for fantasy purposes, the 24-year-old has done just fine. We'll see how he fares when the Bears host New England in Week 7.
report: Mitchell Trubisky completed 22-of-31 passes for 316 yards with three touchdowns and one interception while adding 47 yards on eight carries Sunday in the Bears’ Week 6 loss to Miami.

impact: Trubisky was just 8-for-20 in the first half, but he also made important plays in big spots including a Hail Mary which fell just inches short on the final play. He converted two third downs early in the game on scrambles, and he did even better on the third drive, making the Patriots pay for a fumble on a spectacular "eight-yard" touchdown scramble in which he escaped several defenders in the backfield. He continued to hurt the Patriots with his legs early in the second half, scrambling for 39 yards down to the one-yard line on the opening touchdown drive. The scrambles eventually dried up, however, and Trubisky struggled to get anything going down the field. His risky throws caught up to him on an interception near the end of the third quarter, and he was picked again early in the fourth on an underthrown pass. He did find Trey Burton for a touchdown late and connected on the Hail Mary, but this was not a good showing. He will look to rebound next week against the Jets.
report: Mitchell Trubisky completed 26-of-50 attempts for 333 yards, two touchdowns, and two interceptions in the Bears' Week 7 loss to the Patriots, adding 81 yards and a touchdown on six carries.

impact: Hill took a helmet to his right knee early in the third quarter and was immediately ruled out for the remainder of the game. That is never a good sign. Hill was involved on both offense and special teams before going down, blocking a punt and rushing the ball four times for 25 yards. He added a six-yard reception. A long-term loss would increase the need for Sony Michel (knee) to get cleared.
report: Patriots RB Jeremy Hill was forced from Sunday's game against the Patriots with a knee injury and will not return.

impact: All of his catches came after halftime as the Cardinals were forced to air it out trailing by 21. Seals-Jones was the intended receiver on Sam Bradford’s interception in the second half, which seemed to be a miscommunication. He also dropped a would-be touchdown in the fourth quarter, though Bradford could have placed the ball better. It was a rough opener for the second-year tight end, though his workload was somewhat encouraging. RSJ should probably be avoided next week in a difficult matchup against the Rams.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones chipped in with three catches for 19 yards on six targets Sunday in the Cardinals’ Week 1 loss to the Redskins.

impact: It is a disappointing line for Seals-Jones, but it is not his fault. Arizona's passing game is comatose with Sam Bradford under center. Unfortunately, Seals-Jones will not be a fantasy option until that changes, especially with Jermaine Gresham on the way back.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones hauled in 4-of-6 targets for 17 yards in the Cardinals' Week 2 loss to the Rams.

impact: Seals-Jones made his presence felt early with a 35-yard score down the left side where he was left all alone by the Chicago defense and walked into the end zone. His failed to convert his other two targets for receptions. Jermaine Gresham made a return on Sunday and drew a pair of targets as he will cut into a small portion of Seals-Jones' opportunity, which wasn't exactly strong to begin with. Seals-Jones now has eight catches for 61 yards through three games.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones caught 1-of-3 targets for 35 yards and a touchdown in Sunday's Week 3 loss to the Bears.

impact: The highlight of his day came on a 31-yard catch down the right sideline in which Josh Rosen put right on the money. It was second consecutive game in which Seals-Jones had a 30-yard reception. Through four weeks, Seals-Jones has reeled in 10-of-19 targets for 123 yards and a touchdowns. He will enter Week 5 as a TE2 option against the 49ers.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones caught 2-of-4 targets for 52 yards in Sunday's Week 4 loss to the Seahawks.

impact: Just brutal. RSJ still carries mild streaming appeal at an injury-ravaged fantasy position, though obviously the early returns for him have not been encouraging. The second-year tight end will look to rebound from Sunday's 0-for next time out against the Vikings.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones didn’t catch any of his six targets Sunday in the Cardinals’ Week 5 win over San Francisco.

impact: It's a solid rebound after Jones was held without a catch on six targets last week. He did almost all of his damage early before the Cardinals offense stalled out in the second half. Seals-Jones' highlight was a jump ball over Harrison Smith for 40 yards. He's a TE2 for Thursday night's matchup against the Broncos.
report: Ricky Seals-Jones caught 5-of-6 passes for 69 yards in Week 6 against the Vikings.

impact: The Pats were dialing up some exotic runs but predictably could not get Patterson going as a pass catcher. No one can. Patterson isn't going to make a realistic push for fantasy value the final three weeks of Julian Edelman's suspension.
report: Cordarrelle Patterson rushed three times for 13 yards in the Patriots' Week 1 win over the Texans, adding a six-yard reception.

impact: Patterson set up the Bears’ first touchdown with a fumble on a kickoff return, but he made up for it in the second quarter. With the Patriots down 17-7, Patterson took a kickoff 95 yards to the house to close the deficit and turn the game around. Despite the big special teams play, he has no value in standard fantasy leagues.
report: Cordarrelle Patterson recorded a 95-yard kick-return touchdown in the Patriots' Week 7 win over the Bears.

impact: Suddenly a Dolphin a few weeks ago, O'Leary now has five catches over his past two games. He should stay involved for the Dolphins' Week 8 Thursday night game, as both Albert Wilson (hip) and Kenny Stills (leg) are banged up.
report: Nick O'Leary caught 2-of-3 targets for 23 yards in the Dolphins' Week 7 loss to the Lions.

impact: The Dolphins appear to be using a three-way rotation behind Kenny Stills, with Grant, Albert Wilson, and Danny Amendola vying for targets.  It's a tough situation to bank on from a fantasy football standpoint.
report: Jakeem Grant caught 5-of-7 targets for 38 yards in the Dolphins' Week 1 win over the Titans.

impact: Grant led the Dolphins in Week 1 targets with 7, then took a backseat against the Jets.  He is the No. 4 receiver behind Kenny Stills, Danny Amendola, and Albert Wilson, and DeVante Parker could be activated at any time.
report: Jakeem Grant caught 2-of-4 targets for 37 yards in the Dolphins' Week 2 win over the Jets.

impact: That's maximizing your opportunities. The highlight was a 52-yard score Grant caught from
report: Jakeem Grant caught 2-of-3 targets for 70 yards and two touchdowns in the Dolphins' Week 3 win over the Raiders.

impact: Even with DeVante Parker (quad) sidelined, gadget player Grant was invisible. He has 12 touches through four games. Grant offers rare burst and explosion, but his production will be too scattershot to predict in the Dolphins' low-volume offense.
report: Jakeem Grant caught 2-of-2 targets for 17 yards in the Dolphins' Week 4 loss to the Patriots.

impact: Grant's targets have been in steady decline the last two weeks. He managed a 71-yard punt return touchdown, but he doesn't have much of a role on offense.
report: Jakeem Grant was held without a catch in Week 5 against the Bengals.

impact: Grant was questionable for this game after battling a shoulder injury throughout the week. The injury didn't seem to bother him, though obviously he wasn’t a big factor in this one. Grant won’t be a fantasy option against Detroit in Week 7.
report: Jakeem Grant brought in three-of-four targets for 32 yards Sunday in the Dolphins’ Week 6 win over the Bears.

impact: Grant has just 84 yards receiving over his past four games but will likely be needed for a bigger role in Week 8. Both Albert Wilson and Kenny Stills got banged up against the Lions, and the Dolphins are headed on a short week for Thursday Night Football. Grant is a waiver wire add to keep in mind.
report: Jakeem Grant caught 2-of-2 targets for 32 yards in the Dolphins' Week 7 loss to the Lions.

impact: Osweiler was not sacked. Making his first start for the Dolphins in place of an injured Ryan Tannehill, Osweiler was his usual head-scratching self in the first half but woke up by contributing 266 yards on 16-of-25 passing after the break. Brock had his most success throwing to Albert Wilson, who erupted for a pair of second-half touchdowns including a 75-yarder to tie the game with time winding down in the fourth quarter. Osweiler is now 3-0 against the Bears for his career. He's the first Dolphins signal-caller to reach the 300-yard mark in passing yards since Jay Cutler reached that threshold in Week 9 last season. If Tannehill's shoulder is still an issue, Osweiler could see the field again next week against the Lions.
report: Brock Osweiler completed 28-of-44 passes for a career-high 380 yards with three touchdowns and two interceptions while adding eight yards on two carries Sunday in the Dolphins’ Week 6 win over the Bears.

impact: The two-score day was Osweiler's second straight in place of Ryan Tannehill. Frankly, Osweiler has looked better than Tannehill. Both his scores were dimes delivered into the end zone. With the Dolphins playing on Thursday Night Football in Week 8, Tannehill seems unlikely to get cleared. Despite his good play — relatively speaking — Osweiler will remain a last-gasp QB2, especially since the Dolphins will likely be without Albert Wilson (hip). Wilson went down in the first half Sunday.
report: Brock Osweiler completed 22-of-31 passes for 239 yards and two touchdowns in the Dolphins' 32-21, Week 7 loss to the Lions.

impact: Peterman was a disaster in his third career start, leading the Bills to no scoring drives and zero first downs in the first half. He threw for just 24 yards before getting pulled. Peterman looked completely lost, throwing both of his interceptions directly to the Ravens and taking three sacks. Josh Allen replaced Peterman in the third quarter and should remain the starter going forward.
report: Nathan Peterman was benched in the third quarter of Sunday's Week 1 game against Baltimore.

impact: Things started well for Peterman. Following a Texans fumble, Peterman led a touchdown drive he capped with a nice throw to Zay Jones in the back corner of the end zone to give the Bills the lead. It went downhill from there, however. After the Texans tied the game with under two minutes left, Peterman threw a horrific pick-six which gave Houston the lead. He followed that up with another bad interception on the next drive to end the game. If Allen is forced to miss time, Buffalo probably would be suited going with newly-signed Derek Anderson next week against the Colts.
report: Playing in relief of Josh Allen, Nathan Peterman completed 6-of-12 passes for 61 yards, one touchdown, and two interceptions in the Bills' Week 6 loss to the Texans.
